th-ireland-u20s-3862614-Feb2018/\n |title=Ireland U20s scrum-half O'Sullivan comes from a strong Meath GAA family\n |last=\n |first=\n |date=21 February 2018\n |website=www.the42.ie\n |publisher=\n |access-date=31 October 2019\n |quote= }}</ref> - Current [[Leinster Rugby]] player\n* [[David Shanahan (rugby union)|David Shanahan]] - Current [[Ulster Rugby]] player\n* [[James Hart (rugby union)|James Hart]] - Current [[Biarritz Olympique]] rugby player\n\n===Other Sports===\n* [[Alec O'Riordan]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cricketeurope.com/IRELAND/PLAYERS/487/index.shtml |title=Player profile: Alec O'Riordan  |publisher=CricketEurope |accessdate=2018-10-22}}</ref> \u2013 cricketer\n* [[Frank Miller (Irish cricketer)|Frank Miller]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cricketeurope.com/IRELAND/PLAYERS/447/index.shtml |title=Player profile: Frank Joseph Miller |publisher=CricketEurope |accessdate=2018-11-02}}</ref> - cricketer\n* [[Cathal Pendred]] \u2013 retired [[mixed martial artist]] in the [[Ultimate Fighting Championship|UFC]] and actor<ref>{{cite web|title=Cathal Pendred UFC Profile|url=http://www.ufc.com/fighter/cathal-pendred?id=}}</ref>\n* [[Frank Winder]]{{Citation needed|date=April 2015}} \u2013 [[rock climbing]]\n* [[Paul Corry]] \u2013 soccer\n* [[Kevin Grogan]] - soccer\n* [[Pat Taaffe]] Cheltenham Gold Cup winner on the horse [[Arkle]] and [[Tom Taaffe]] - jockey and trainer\n\n===Olympians===\n* [[Noel Purcell (water polo player)|Noel Purcell]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jesuitcommunicationcentre.newsweaver.com/Newsletter/a6ry8fbvst9|title=Around the Province|publisher=}}</ref> \u2013 [[water polo]], rugby union, international rugby union referee and Olympian with two different countries\n* [[Peter Coghlan]]<ref name=\"Coghlan ready to reap the rewards\">{{cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/sport/coghlan-ready-to-reap-the-rewards-1.217879?mode=sample&auth-failed=1&pw-origin=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.irishtimes.com%2Fsport%2Fcoghlan-ready-to-reap-the-rewards-1.217879|title=Coghlan ready to reap the rewards|publisher=The Irish Times}}</ref> - Competed for Ireland in the [[Sydney 2000]] Olympics in the [[110 metres hurdles]]\n* [[Cian O'Connor]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/determination-that-took-a-boy-and-a-dream-to-the-glory-of-olympic-gold-26224042.html|title=Determination that took a boy and a dream to the glory of Olympic Gold|publisher=Irish Independent}}</ref> \u2013 Olympian ([[2012 Summer Olympics|London 2012]], [[Athens 2004]] \u2013 [[Equestrianism|equestrian]])\n* [[Barry Murphy (swimmer)|Barry Murphy]]{{Citation needed|date=April 2015}} \u2013 Olympian ([[2012 Summer Olympics|London 2012]] - swimming)\n\n===Gaelic Sports===\n* [[Se\u00e1n Boylan]] \u2013 former [[Meath GAA]] football manager, [[International rules football|international rules]] coach and traditional medical herbalist<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irishlifeandlore.com/product/se%C3%A1n-boylan-b-1943/|title=Sean Boylan|publisher=Irish Life and Lore|date=2017-02-02}}</ref> \n* [[Ger Brennan]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/social-affairs/religion-and-beliefs/ger-brennan-says-time-for-young-people-to-learn-more-about-faith-1.1661808|title=Ger Brennan says time for young people to learn more about faith|publisher=}}</ref> \u2013 Former Dublin and St.Vincents [[Gaelic Athletic Association|GAA]] player and member of the 2003 Senior Rugby team 1st XV\n* Dr. [[Jack McCaffrey]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gaa.ie/features/feature/club-jack-mccaffrey-clontarf-109724/|publisher=GAA.ie|date=2015-03-12}}</ref>  \u2013 [[Gaelic Athletic Association|GAA]], 2015 FOTY and [[Clontarf GAA]] player\n\n===Business and professional===\n* [[Arthur Cox (lawyer)|Arthur Cox]] \u2013 founder of eponymous law firm and member of the Seanad\n* [[Garrett Kelleher]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.ie/lifestyle/he-reached-for-the-sky-26690172.html|title=He reached for the sky - Independent.ie|publisher=}}</ref> \u2013 construction\n* [[Michael Scott (architect)|Michael Scott]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jesuit.ie/news/refurbished-belvedere-house-hold-art-exhibition/|title=Refurbished Belvedere House to hold art exhibition - Jesuits Ireland|date=28 January 2015|publisher=}}</ref> \u2013 architect\n* [[Sam Stephenson]] \u2013 architect<ref>{{cite news|title=Archived version of Sam Stephenson Obituary|url=https://groups.google.com/forum/#!topic/alt.obituaries/0iGwGfGNw2Q|accessdate=8 April 2015|work=The Times (London)}}</ref>\n* [[Alfred Edwin Jones]] \u2013 architect<ref>{{cite web|title=Dictionary of Irish Architects 1720-1940|url=http://www.dia.ie/architects/view/2840/JONES-ALFREDEDWIN|publisher=Irish Architectural Archive|accessdate=8 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Broadcasting===\n* [[John Bowman (broadcaster)|John Bowman]] \u2013 broadcaster<ref name=\"Irish Times, 2002\"/>\n* [[Ian Dempsey]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.ie/lifestyle/health/diabetes-ian-dempsey-on-his-life-sentence-26846322.html|title=Diabetes: Ian Dempsey on his life sentence - Independent.ie|publisher=}}</ref> \u2013 radio DJ with [[Today FM]] (Did not graduate)\n* [[Henry Kelly]] \u2013 BBC and RTE television presenter, radio disc jockey and the person on whom the character Henry Sellers in [[Father Ted]] was based<ref>http://www.independent.ie/breaking-news/irish-news/wogan-death-a-shock-and-a-shame-says-friend-henry-kelly-34411101.html{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* Sir [[Terry Wogan]] \u2013 BBC and RTE broadcaster <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.catholicireland.net/belvedere-college-pays-tribute-terry-wogan/|title=Belvedere College pays tribute to Terry Wogan|publisher=CatholicIreland.net|date=2016-02-03}}</ref>\n\n===Peers===\n* [[Edward Melchior Pakenham|Edward Pakenham, Lord Silchester]]{{Citation needed|date=April 2015}} \n* [[Thomas Pakenham (historian)|Thomas Pakenham]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/meetings-with-a-remarkable-man-thomas-pakenham-31520204.html|title=Meetings with a remarkable man... Thomas Pakenham - Independent.ie|publisher=}}</ref> 8th Earl of Longford \u2013 historian\n\n===Other===\n* [[Edward Joseph Garland]] - Canadian [[Member of Parliament]] for Alberta and diplomat\n* [[:no:Arthur Joseph Beveridge|Dr. Arthur Beveridge]] {{post-nominals|OBE}} - British military officer and Military Cross Holder, [[War Cross (Norway)|Norwegian War Cross]] holder and honorary physician to [[George VI]]\n* [[Michael Joseph Hogan]] - [[Chief Justice of the Supreme Court of Hong Kong]] for 14 years\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Notable faculty==\n* [[\u00c9amon de Valera]] \u2013 Taoiseach and President of Ireland{{Citation needed|date = November 2017}}\n* [[George Dempsey (teacher)|George Dempsey]] \u2013 model for Mr. Tate in ''Joyce's Portrait of an Artist'' and after whom a stream class \"Dempsey\" was named for a number of years\n* [[Phil Conway]]<ref name=\"Coghlan ready to reap the rewards\"/> - Former PE teacher who competed for Ireland at the [[1972 Summer Olympics]] in Munich in the Shot Putt\n* [[Michael Morrison (priest)|Fr. Michael Morrison]] - photographer at the liberation of Bergen Belsen concentration camp\n* Fr. [[Peter McVerry]] - homelessness campaigner in Dublin\n* [[John Conmee]]\n* [[Charlie Hallows]]\n* [[Robin Waters]]\n* [[Michael Morrison (priest)]]\n* [[Patrick G. Kennedy]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Victoria Crosses by school]]\n* [[List of alumni of Jesuit educational institutions]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.belvederecollege.ie/ Belvedere College website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090309051148/http://www.belvounion.ie/ Belvedere College Past Pupils Union website]\n\n{{Jesuits in Ireland}}\n{{Schools and colleges in County Dublin}}\n{{Private schools in the Republic of Ireland}}\n\n[[Category:Boys' schools in the Republic of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Secondary schools in Dublin (city)]]\n[[Category:Private schools in the Republic of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Jesuit secondary schools in Ireland]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1832]]\n", "name_user": "2001:bb6:34e:e058:ac17:548e:3a1:18f2", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Belvedere_College"}
{"title_page": "Benjamin Bryant (broadcaster)", "text_new": "{{For|other people with the same name|Benjamin Bryant (disambiguation){{!}}Benjamin Bryant}}\n{{short description|American writer, artist, and broadcaster|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Benjamin Bryant\n| image              = Benjamin Bryant - 2018 Daytime Emmys.jpg\n| caption            = Bryant at the 45th Daytime Emmy Nominee Reception\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1977|01|13}}\n| birth_place        = [[Nuremberg]], [[West Germany]]\n| residence          = [[Washington, D.C.]]\n| nationality        = American\n| citizenship        = \n| education          = [[University of the Incarnate Word]] <small>([[Master of Science|MS]])</small>\n\n[[University of the Incarnate Word]] <small>([[Master of Arts|MA]])</small>\n\n[[Excelsior College]] <small>([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])</small>\n\n[[University of Texas at Austin]]\n\n[[Giessen American High School]]\n| occupation         = Writer<br>Broadcaster<br>Television Producer<br>Civil Servant {{small|(past)}}\n| years_active       = 1996\u2013present\n| organization       = United States Coast Guard Auxiliary\n| known_for          = [[2009 Fort Hood shooting|Fort Hood Shooting]] Task Force<br>\n[[Don't Ask, Don't Tell]] DoD Working Group <br>\nMilitary Compensation and Retirement Modernization Commission\n| notable_works      = \"The Brink with Benjamin Bryant: INTERSECTIONS\" {{small|(event podcast)}}\n| television         = ''Journeys Beyond''{{small|(2019\u2013present)}}<br>''The Brink with Benjamin Bryant'' {{small|(2018\u2013present)}}<br>''[[Anacostia (web series)|Anacostia]]'' {{small|(2016-present)}}<br> ''[[America Tonight]]'' {{small|(guest, 2012\u20132013)}}<br>\n| mother             = Renee Bryant\n| father             = [[Albert Bryant, Jr.]]\n| relatives          = [[Lori Bryant-Woolridge]]\n| awards             = Telly Award<br />Hermes Creative Award<br />AVA Digital Awards<br>MarCom Award<br />Silver Inkwell Award<br>Davey Award<br>Communicator Award<br>Paul R. Ellis Award\n}}\n\n'''Benjamin Bryant''' (born 1977) is an [[Americans|American]] writer, artist, and broadcaster. He is the former co-executive producer of the [[Daytime Emmy]]-winning drama series [[Anacostia (web series)|Anacostia]] (where he occasionally appeared in front of the camera), and current host of the interview program and [[podcast]] \u201cThe Brink with Benjamin Bryant\u201d and co-host upcoming travel [[docuseries]] \"Journeys Beyond.\" He has produced several television and streaming series, specials, and a series of holiday films.\n\nPreviously, Bryant served in senior staff positions on multiple high profile task forces and commissions during the [[Barack Obama]] administration, including the [[The Pentagon|Pentagon]]\u2019s [[2009 Fort Hood shooting|Fort Hood Shooting]] Task Force, \u201c[[Don't Ask, Don't Tell Repeal Act of 2010|Don\u2019t Ask, Don\u2019t Tell\u201d Repeal]] Working Group, and the two-year Military Compensation and Retirement Modernization Commission, for which he was the commission\u2019s final spokesperson. In 2011, the [[Dolph Briscoe Center for American History]] at the [[University of Texas at Austin]] announced the formal acquisition of several of Bryant's papers, notes, and recordings related to his historic work for the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|White House]] and [[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defense]].\n\nIn addition to his work as a journalist and broadcaster, Bryant has appeared as a guest and interview subject in the media throughout his career, including multiple appearances on the nightly news program [[America Tonight]].\n\n== Early life and education ==\n\nBryant was born in [[Nuremberg]], [[Germany]] to American parents in a multi-generational military family. His father, [[Brigadier general (United States)|Brigadier General]] [[Albert Bryant Jr.|Albert Bryant Jr]], is known for his role in the immediate military response to [[September 11 attacks|9/11]], service as Assistant Division Commander of the [[4th Infantry Division (United States)|4th Infantry Division]] during the [[Iraq War]], and was the highest-ranking American service-member at the time of his service as part of [[NATO]]\u2019s [[Kosovo Force]]. He is the grandson of Brigadier General Albert Bryant, Sr., recipient of the [[Congressional Gold Medal]] and a former [[Montford Point Marine Association|Montford Point Marine]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/history/2020/04/12/iwo-jima-veteran-coronavirus-albert-bryant/|title=He saw the flag raised at Iwo Jima. Now, at 94, he watches the nation fight a deadly virus.|last=Shapiro|first=Ian|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref> and Army Brigadier General Richard Saxton. He is also the nephew of [[Emmy Award|Emmy]]-winning writer and speaker [[Lori Bryant-Woolridge]].\n\nBryant graduated from [[Giessen American High School]] in [[Giessen]], [[Germany]] in 1994, commencing study at the [[University of Texas at Austin]], that same year.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thebzgroup.com/about-us/leadership/|title=Leadership|website=thebzgroup.com|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref>  At Texas, he studied journalism and communication studies from 1994-1998, when an extended illness led to medical withdrawal prior to graduation. When professional demands later prevented a full-time return to Texas, Bryant completed a [[Bachelor of Science]] degree from [[New York (state)|New York]]\u2019s [[Excelsior College]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://alumnius.net/excelsior_college-8954-2#id11065057|title=Alumni US {{!}} Excelsior College, Albany, New York Area|website=alumnius.net|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Bryant earned two Master\u2019s degrees, a [[Master of Arts]] in Administration and a [[Master of Science]] in Organizational Development and Leadership, from the [[University of the Incarnate Word]] in [[San Antonio]], [[Texas]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://alumnius.net/university_of_the_in-9551-year-2015#id11065057|title=Alumni US {{!}} University of the Incarnate Word (2015)|website=alumnius.net|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref>\n\n== Journalism and broadcasting ==\nIn 1996, Bryant was serving as a [[radio news]] intern at [[Austin, Texas|Austin]] radio station [[KKMJ]] when the [[Olympic Bomber|Atlanta Olympic Bombing]] occurred.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Who was that voice?|last=Grieg|first=Jane|date=August 1996|work=Austin American-Statesman|access-date=|month=|year=}}</ref> His impromptu overnight coverage gathered attention from the public and [[Austin American-Statesman]] columnist Jane Grieg, leading to a full-time role consisting of on-air roles at KKMJ and named Program Director, with news and local programming responsibility, of its sister station, ABC Radio affiliate [[KJCE]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://benjaminbryant.net/clipbook/ARSNewsletter.pdf|title=Americans on the Rise|last=|first=|date=July 1996|work=ARS Newsletter|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=The JUICE changes its on-air fare|last=Herndon|first=John|date=October 1996|work=Austin American-Statesman|access-date=}}</ref> Bryant also hosted KJCE\u2019s weekly Sunday morning current affairs program.\n\nAfter leaving Austin and the radio industry, Bryant worked as a freelance journalist<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/78606345/Montgomery-Gazette-Coverage-of-Maryland-Regional-AIDS-Conference|title=Montgomery Gazette Coverage of Maryland Regional AIDS Conference|website=Scribd|language=en|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref> and columnist before focusing on public relations and crisis communications consulting for public and private sector clients, though in those capacities, he served as writer and editor of multiple public-facing government publications, including the ''Deepwater News'' and ''FHP&R: Force Health Protection & Readiness'' magazine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://issuu.com/thebzgroup/docs/fhprmag_fall2007|title=Force Health Protection & Readiness Magazine - Fall 2007|website=Issuu|language=en|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref> He returned to broadcasting as the host of the \u201cBZCast\u201d podcast in 2017, including an award-winning exploration of leaking and whistleblowing in the federal government,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thebzgroup.com/the-bz-cast-leaking-or-whistleblowing/|title=The BZ Cast \u2013 Leaking or Whistleblowing?|website=thebzgroup.com|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref> and in a more significant way in 2018 with the launch of non-profit media platform [http://www.thebzmp.com BZ/MP] and the debut of the \u201c[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VuMyz4eFW8I The Brink with Benjamin Bryant],\u201d a series of one-on-one interview specials focusing on [[Washington, D.C.|Washington D.C.]] notables, and its spin-off serialized investigative podcast, \u201c[https://thebzmp.podbean.com/ The Brink with Benjamin Bryant: INTERSECTIONS],\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thebzmp.com/bzmpradio20181213-brinkreturns/|title=THE BRINK Returns with \"Intersections\" in 2019 - BZ/MP Radio|date=2018-12-13|website=BZ/MP|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref> both of which have since received a number of awards and honors, including several for Bryant as producer and host. In 2018, Bryant also appeared in an award-winning, non-partisan public service announcement entitled \"The One Place Everyone is Equal.\"<ref>{{Citation|last=BZ/MP - The Bryant Zamberlan Media Project|title=The One Place Everyone is Equal: The Ballot Box|date=2019-01-23|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IjupfK9zKeI|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref>\n\n== Military and government ==\n\nBryant has served in a variety of communications roles for the military services, including as a speechwriter for Rear Admiral Patrick Stillman of the [[United States Coast Guard]], and communications advisor for the Hon. [[James I. Finley|James Finley]] and then as a speechwriter and communications advisor for several senior military leaders, and has worked on multiple high-profile roles on Presidential task forces and commissions, including the Pentagon\u2019s [[2009 Fort Hood shooting|Fort Hood Shooting Task Force]], \u201c[[Don't ask, don't tell|Don\u2019t Ask, Don\u2019t Tell\u201d Repeal Working Group]], and the Military Compensation and Retirement Modernization Commission, for which he served as the agency\u2019s final [[spokesperson]]. On multiple occasions, Bryant appeared as a guest on  the nightly news program [[America Tonight]], hosted by journalist [[Joie Chen]], speaking to military issues in the news,.<ref>{{Citation|title=America Tonight : ALJAZAM : September 17, 2013 4:00am-5:01am EDT|date=2013-09-17|url=http://archive.org/details/ALJAZAM_20130917_080000_America_Tonight|others=ALJAZAM|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=America Tonight : ALJAZAM : April 3, 2014 12:00am-1:01am EDT|date=2014-04-03|url=http://archive.org/details/ALJAZAM_20140403_040000_America_Tonight|others=ALJAZAM|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=America Tonight : ALJAZAM : April 4, 2014 4:00am-5:01am EDT|date=2014-04-04|url=http://archive.org/details/ALJAZAM_20140404_080000_America_Tonight|others=ALJAZAM|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref>\n\nBryant's work as a government consultant and contracted advisor also includes substantial efforts in the public health arena. Bryant worked as a communications advisor to the [[United States Department of Defense|DoD]] Force Health Protection and Readiness agency, serving as speechwriter to [[Deputy Assistant Secretary of Defense]] Ellen Embrey, and supervising a redesign and relaunch of the agency's globally-distributed ''FHP&R: Force Health Protection'' full-color print magazine. In 2011, Bryant led a team of Bryant Zamberlan Group researchers, analysts, and writers (including former acting [[Surgeon General of the United States Army]] [[Major general (United States)|Major General]] Gail Pollock) conducting a federally-funded assessment of community preparedness and the effectiveness of [[public health]] outreach and education regarding [[Influenza pandemic|pandemic influenza]] health risks in the [[Virginia Beach, Virginia|Virginia Beach]] area. Bryant also authored the team's final report.\n\n==== Task Forces and Commissions ====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Name\n!Leadership\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|2009-2010\n|[[2009 Fort Hood shooting|Department of Defense<br>Fort Hood Shooting Task Force]]\n|Hon. [[Togo D. West Jr.|Togo D. West, Jr.]],<br>Adm. [[Vern Clark]]\n|Managing Editor,<br>Writing and Admin Team Lead\n|\n|-\n|2010\n|US Air Force Fort Hood Task Force Follow-on\n|Sec. [[Michael B. Donley]]\n|Senior Writer,<br>Writing Team Lead\n|\n|-\n|2010\n|\"[[Don't ask, don't tell|Don't Ask, Don't Tell]]\" Comprehensive Review Working Group\n|Hon. [[Jeh Johnson]],\nGen. [[Carter Ham]]\n|Lead Editor,<br>Editorial and Production Lead\n|\n|-\n|2011\n|[[Virginia Department of Health]]/[[Virginia Beach, Virginia|VA Beach]]<br>[[Influenza pandemic|Pandemic Influenza]] Program Assessment\n|Benjamin Bryant\n|Executive Director,<br>Report Author\n|\n|-\n|2013-2016\n|Military Compensation and Retirement Modernization Commission\n|Hon. Al Maldon\n|Assoc. Director, Public Relations and Outreach {{small|(2015-2016)}},<br>Lead Writer and Editor and<br>Editorial and Production Lead {{small|(2013-2015)}}\n|\n|-\n|}\n\nIn 2011, news reports covered Bryant and Thomas Zamberlan's donation of their original editor's copies from several Presidential and DoD task forces to the [[Smithsonian Institution]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.macombdaily.com/news/work-of-sterling-heights-native-added-to-smithsonian/article_b0eb5ded-3191-5597-8138-327ec13c91f5.html|title=Work of Sterling Heights native added to Smithsonian|last=KASZUBSKI|first=DEBRA|website=Macomb Daily|language=en|access-date=2019-05-24}}</ref> That same year, the [[Dolph Briscoe Center for American History]] at Bryant's alma mater [[University of Texas at Austin]], announced the acquisition of Bryant's personal notes, papers, and recorded recollections related to his work on the historic Fort Hood investigation and \"Don't Ask, Don't Tell\" repeals and their intention to make them available to researchers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://legacy.lib.utexas.edu/taro/utcah/03175/03175-P.html|title=A Guide to the Benjamin Bryant Papers, 2010|website=legacy.lib.utexas.edu|access-date=2019-05-24}}</ref>\n\nSince 2010, Bryant has been an Auxiliarist in the [[United States Coast Guard Auxiliary]], including service as a Flotilla Staff Officer.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.linkedin.com/in/benbryant13|title=Benjamin Bryant|website=LinkedIn|access-date=March 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Arts ==\n\nIn addition to his news and documentary work, Bryant has done substantial work in the arts, including film, television, and visual arts.\n\n=== Film and Television ===\n[[File:Anacostia S5 Interior3.jpg|thumb|Benjamin Bryant with actress Marion Akpan on the set of [[Anacostia (web series)|Anacostia]] in 2017]]\nBryant began producing narrative television and film projects in 2016, first joining the Daytime Emmy-winning, six-time nominated, digital series ''[[Anacostia (web series)|Anacostia]]'', from creator Anthony Anderson at the start of its fifth season, as a supervising producer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://benjaminbryant.kinja.com/anacostia-showrunner-anthony-anderson-talks-tackling-ma-1792659968|title=ANACOSTIA's Anthony Anderson tackles male/male rape (and gentrification!) in season five, and feels the responsibilities of African American storytelling|last=Bryant|first=Benjamin|website=Benjamin Bryant|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref><ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm8616001/|title=Benjamin Bryant|website=IMDb|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref> Beginning with episode five, Bryant was named co-[[executive producer]] of the series, a role he continued in until September 2019.<ref name=\":12\" /><ref name=\":22\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/gp/video/detail/B07H5VP6TF/ref=atv_dp_season_select_atf/139-3312839-3468708|title=Amazon.com: Watch Anacostia {{!}} Prime Video|website=www.amazon.com|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref> He also occasionally recurred on the series in the role of news anchor \"James Vance,\" an homage to the late Washington D.C. news anchor [[Jim Vance]].<ref name=\":12\" />\n\nIn 2019, his company, the Bryant Zamberlan Group, partnered with Gemelli Films and writer-director Candice Cain to produce the \"Candy Cain\" series of holiday films,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.welovesoaps.net/2019/08/Candy-Cain-holiday-films.html|title='Candy Cain' Holiday Trio of Films Features Former Soap Stars Patrick Muldoon, Carrie Genzel, Terri Garber, Jennifer Bassey, Cynthia Gibb|last=Newcomb|first=Roger|language=en|access-date=2019-09-11}}</ref> completing work on the holiday romances ''Ivy & Mistletoe'', starring [[Cody Calafiore]], [[Carrie Genzel]], and [[Cynthia Gibb]]; Destination: Christmas, starring Calafiore, [[Clayton Snyder]], and [[Abigail Hawk]]; and ''Painting Christmas'', starring Calafiore, Genzel, [[Patrick Muldoon]], [[Frank Whaley]], [[Terri Garber]], and [[Jennifer Bassey]],<ref name=\":12\" /> with the Global Genesis Group handling distribution.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/news/ni62583210|title='Candy Cain' Holiday Trio of Films|last=|first=|date=|website=IMDb|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-11}}</ref> Bryant, who served as the supervising producer on the films, also makes a cameo appearance in each one.<ref name=\":12\"/> Bryant also served as an Associate Producer on Cain's ''Joy & Hope'' a western-themed romance co-starring [[Vivica A. Fox]].\n\nIn September 2019, Bryant and travel writer Olivia Taylor announced on their respective social media platforms that they would co-host an upcoming travel show for the 2019-2020 season, titled \"Journey's Beyond.\"<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/poop.love/posts/10214112602995280|title=I'm hosting a new travel show|last=|first=|date=|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-11}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/bzbenbryant/posts/2515270521893195|title=A little tease for you|last=Bryant|first=Benjamin|date=|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B2OMBilhy_0/|title=Benjamin Bryant on Instagram: \"All I can share for now, but watch this space for details on my newest adventure!\"|last=|first=|date=|website=Instagram|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-11}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2020, production in [[Las Vegas]], [[Nevada]] was paused on Bryant's sports mockumentary ''Aidy Kane'' due to the [[COVID-19]] pandemic.\n\n==== Film ====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|1996\n|''[[Courage Under Fire]]''\n|Soldier (uncredited)\n|<ref name=\":12\"/>\n|-\n|2019\n|''Ivy & Mistletoe''\n|Supervising Producer, ''Air Traveler'' (cameo)\n|<ref name=\":12\"/>\n|-\n|2019\n|''Destination: Christmas''\n|Supervising Producer, ''Airline Employee'' (cameo)\n|<ref name=\":12\"/>\n|-\n|2019\n|''Painting Christmas''\n|Supervising Producer, ''Waterbury Coach'' (cameo)\n|<ref name=\":12\"/>\n|-\n|2020\n|''Aidy Kane''\n|Director, \u201cPhineas Strong\u201d\n|<ref>{{Citation|title=Aidy Kane|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt10868884/|access-date=2019-09-11}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==== Television and Digital Streaming ====\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|2016-2019\n|''[[Anacostia (web series)|Anacostia]]''\n|co-Executive Producer, \u201cJames Vance\u201d\n|<ref name=\":12\"/><ref name=\":22\"/>\n|-\n|2018-2019\n|''The Brink with Benjamin Bryant''\n|Executive Producer, Host\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thebzmp.com/bzmptv20181201-bzmpdc-brinkspecial/|title=WATCH NOW: The Brink's BZ/MP D.C. interviews come to life!|date=2018-12-01|website=BZ/MP|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref>\n|-\n|2018\n|''Unraveling Knots: The Journey Begins''\n|Executive Producer, Host\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thebzmp.com/bzmptv20181231-knotsjourney/|title=WATCH NOW: Unraveling Knots: The Journey Begins - BZ/MP TV|date=2018-12-31|website=BZ/MP|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref>\n|-\n|2018\n|''BZ Explains! Welcome to the Show''\n|The Narrator (character)\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thebzmp.com/bzmptv20181231-openingcredits/|title=WATCH NOW: Welcome to the Show: TV's First Impressions - BZ/MP TV|date=2018-12-31|website=BZ/MP|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref>\n|-\n|-\n|2019\n|Journeys Beyond\n|Executive Producer, co-Host\n|<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":8\" />\n|}\n\n=== Painting and photography ===\n\nIn the 2010s, Bryant has also worked intermittently as professional artist, photographer, and painter, signing his work as \"Ben Bryant.<nowiki>''</nowiki> His pieces featured and sold through the [[Saatchi Gallery]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.saatchiart.com/benjaminbryant|title=Benjamin Bryant|website=Saatchi Art|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref> In 2018, a whimsical portrait Bryant painted in hours, was featured on the sixth season premiere of \"Anacostia\" (in a roadside shrine honoring a child lost to gun violence).<ref>{{Citation|last=ANACOSTIASERIES|title=ANACOSTIA Season 6 Episode 1 \"Aftermath\"|date=2018-12-30|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Y6jDScxVREk|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref> Shortly after, it became the first of his paintings to sell for more than $1,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.saatchiart.com/art/Painting-Taty-featured-on-the-Emmy-winning-series-Anacostia/1131628/4636336/view|title=Taty (featured on the Emmy-winning series \"Anacostia\") Painting|website=Saatchi Art|language=en|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref> He is also an artistic, commercial, and editorial photographer. The posters for the films ''Destination: Christmas'' and ''Painting Christmas'', which Bryant produced, feature his photography.\n\n== Business ==\n\nSince 2010, Bryant has served as the Managing Partner of the Bryant Zamberlan Group of companies, which include a global communications consultancy and BZ/MP, a non-profit news and media endeavor. In this role, Bryant holds multiple certifications, and has advised and trained senior leaders in the United States Government and international business.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Awards, Honors, and Nominations ==\nBryant has received numerous industry honors and nominations for his work as a journalist, broadcaster, and producer, beginning with two Paul R. Ellis awards from the American Heart Association of Texas in 1996 for writing and producing content to educate the Austin, TX community regarding increased heart disease and stroke risks in minority communities at radio station [[KJCE]].\n\nSince 1999, he has been honored with Communicator, MarCom, Hermes Creative, W3, Davey, AVA, and Silver Inkwell awards for various writing, multimedia, video, and other projects.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://enter.avaawards.com/|title=AVA Digital Awards|website=enter.avaawards.com|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.communicatorawards.com/winners/gallery/|title=Communicator Awards {{!}} Award of Excellence Winners Gallery|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.daveyawards.com/winners/winners/|title=Davey Awards {{!}} Winners|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://enter.hermesawards.com/|title=Hermes Creative Awards|website=enter.hermesawards.com|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref>\n\nAs co-executive producer of the six-time [[Emmy Award|Emmy]] nominated [[Anacostia (web series)|Anacostia]], Bryant received a 2018 [[Indie Series Awards|Indie Series Award]] nomination, Hermes Creative Award, Telly Award, and two consecutive Best Drama Series honors at the Rome Web Awards.\n\nOther notable honors include a 2010 Platinum MarCom \"Special Category\" Award for his work as the Managing Editor of the report of the Fort Hood Task Force, 2012 Davey Award for his appearances on ''America Tonight'', 2019 Communicator Award of Distinction for \"The Brink with Benjamin Bryant\" interview specials; and multiple Platinum AVA and Hermes Creative Awards for \"The Brink with Benjamin Bryant: INTERSECTIONS\" podcast (including honors for writing, hosting, and production).<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIn a year-end feature dedicated to the people and stories who made the year notable, Bryant was named by the Austin American-Statesman as one of its most memorable people in 1996.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Looking Back at the People Who Made 1996 Memorable: 'Familiar Voice'|last=Grieg|first=Jane|date=January 2, 1997|work=Austin American-Statesman|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n\nBryant currently lives in the Washington, D.C. metro area.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n*[[imdbname:8616001|''Benjamin Bryant (II)'' IMDb.com]]\n*{{cite news|url=http://benjaminbryant.net/clipbook/robpatterson0497.html|title=Some Questions: Radio's Benjamin Bryant|last=Patterson|first=Robert|date=1997-04-10|work=[[Austin American-Statesman]]|accessdate=2019-04-13|publisher=[[Cox Media Group]]}}\n* {{cite news|url=http://benjaminbryant.net/clipbook/johnherndon0197.html|title=Radio: Tough Work if You Can Get It|last=Herndon|first=John|date=1997-01-02|work=[[Austin American-Statesman]]|accessdate=2019-04-13|publisher=[[Cox Media Group]]}}\n*[http://www.thebzgroup.com/ ''Bryant Zamberlan Group'']*\n*{{cite news|url=http://www.thebzmp.com/anacostia-showrunner-shakes-up-season-five|title=Anacostia\" showrunner shakes up season five|date=2018-10-08|accessdate=2018-11-23|publisher=|last=|first=|work=}}\n* {{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sVI_91f7JhU|title=Daytime Indulgence Podcast #4: Ben Bryant|last=Hutchison|first=Casey|date=2018-02-06|work=Daytime Indulgence|accessdate=2018-11-23|publisher=}}\n* {{cite news|url=https://player.fm/series/soap-party-2407367/ep-258-anthony-anderson-jennifer-bassey-and-benjamin-bryant-of-anacostia|title=Anthony Anderson, Jennifer Bassey and Benjamin Bryant of Anacostia|last=Mack|first=Candice|date=2018-05-06|work=SoapParty 411|accessdate=2018-11-23|publisher=}}\n* [https://www.facebook.com/bzbenbryant ''Benjamin Bryant official page'' Facebook.com]\n* [https://www.linkedin.com/in/benbryant13 ''Benjamin Bryant'' LinkedIn.com]\n* {{cite news|url=http://www.thebzmp.com/a-right-to-the-city-smithsonian-anacostia-museum|title=A Right to the City Debuts|last=BZ/MP DMV|first=|date=2018-07-21|work=BZ/MP|access-date=|publisher=}}\n*{{cite news|url=https://rebootcamp.militarytimes.com/education-transition/2015/06/26/contractor-jobs-exist-way-out-of-washington|title=Working Way Outside of Washington|last=Stone|first=Adam|date=2015-06-26|work=Military Times|accessdate=2016-05-23|publisher=}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bryant, Benjamin}}\n[[Category:American television news anchors]]\n[[Category:American television reporters and correspondents]]\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American journalists]]\n[[Category:African-American television hosts]]\n[[Category:African-American television personalities]]\n[[Category:American television hosts]]\n[[Category:American male journalists]]\n[[Category:Moody College of Communication alumni]]\n[[Category:Excelsior College alumni]]\n[[Category:University of the Incarnate Word alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Nuremberg]]\n[[Category:People from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:American civil servants]]\n[[Category:20th-century American journalists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American journalists]]\n[[Category:United States Army civilians]]\n[[Category:United States Department of Defense officials]]\n[[Category:American journalists of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:American television journalists]]\n[[Category:American radio DJs]]\n[[Category:American radio news anchors]]\n[[Category:American television producers]]\n[[Category:American painters]]\n[[Category:American press secretaries]]\n[[Category:American men podcasters]]\n[[Category:American podcasters]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|other people with the same name|Benjamin Bryant (disambiguation){{!}}Benjamin Bryant}}\n{{short description|American writer, artist, and broadcaster|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Benjamin Bryant\n| image              = Benjamin Bryant - 2018 Daytime Emmys.jpg\n| caption            = Bryant at the 45th Daytime Emmy Nominee Reception\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1977|01|13}}\n| birth_place        = [[Nuremberg]], [[West Germany]]\n| residence          = [[Washington, D.C.]]\n| nationality        = American\n| citizenship        = \n| education          = [[University of the Incarnate Word]] <small>([[Master of Science|MS]])</small>\n\n[[University of the Incarnate Word]] <small>([[Master of Arts|MA]])</small>\n\n[[Excelsior College]] <small>([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])</small>\n\n[[University of Texas at Austin]]\n\n[[Giessen American High School]]\n| occupation         = Writer<br>Broadcaster<br>Television Producer<br>Civil Servant {{small|(past)}}\n| years_active       = 1996\u2013present\n| organization       = United States Coast Guard Auxiliary\n| known_for          = [[2009 Fort Hood shooting|Fort Hood Shooting]] Task Force<br>\n[[Don't Ask, Don't Tell]] DoD Working Group <br>\nMilitary Compensation and Retirement Modernization Commission\n| notable_works      = \"The Brink with Benjamin Bryant: INTERSECTIONS\" {{small|(event podcast)}}\n| television         = ''Journeys Beyond''{{small|(2019\u2013present)}}<br>''The Brink with Benjamin Bryant'' {{small|(2018\u2013present)}}<br>''[[Anacostia (web series)|Anacostia]]'' {{small|(2016-present)}}<br> ''[[America Tonight]]'' {{small|(guest, 2012\u20132013)}}<br>\n| mother             = Renee Bryant\n| father             = [[Albert Bryant, Jr.]]\n| relatives          = [[Lori Bryant-Woolridge]]\n| awards             = Telly Award<br />Hermes Creative Award<br />AVA Digital Awards<br>MarCom Award<br />Silver Inkwell Award<br>Davey Award<br>Communicator Award<br>Paul R. Ellis Award\n}}\n\n'''Benjamin Bryant''' (born 1977) is an [[Americans|American]] writer, artist, and broadcaster. He is the former co-executive producer of the [[Daytime Emmy]]-winning drama series [[Anacostia (web series)|Anacostia]] (where he occasionally appeared in front of the camera), and current host of the interview program and [[podcast]] \u201cThe Brink with Benjamin Bryant\u201d and co-host upcoming travel [[docuseries]] \"Journeys Beyond.\" He has produced several television and streaming series, specials, and a series of holiday films.\n\nPreviously, Bryant served in senior staff positions on multiple high profile task forces and commissions during the [[Barack Obama]] administration, including the [[The Pentagon|Pentagon]]\u2019s [[2009 Fort Hood shooting|Fort Hood Shooting]] Task Force, \u201c[[Don't Ask, Don't Tell Repeal Act of 2010|Don\u2019t Ask, Don\u2019t Tell\u201d Repeal]] Working Group, and the two-year Military Compensation and Retirement Modernization Commission, for which he was the commission\u2019s final spokesperson. In 2011, the [[Dolph Briscoe Center for American History]] at the [[University of Texas at Austin]] announced the formal acquisition of several of Bryant's papers, notes, and recordings related to his historic work for the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|White House]] and [[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defense]].\n\nIn addition to his work as a journalist and broadcaster, Bryant has appeared as a guest and interview subject in the media throughout his career, including multiple appearances on the nightly news program [[America Tonight]].\n\n== Early life and education ==\n\nBryant was born in [[Nuremberg]], [[Germany]] to American parents in a multi-generational military family. His father, [[Brigadier general (United States)|Brigadier General]] [[Albert Bryant Jr.|Albert Bryant Jr]], is known for his role in the immediate military response to [[September 11 attacks|9/11]], service as Assistant Division Commander of the [[4th Infantry Division (United States)|4th Infantry Division]] during the [[Iraq War]], and was the highest-ranking American service-member at the time of his service as part of [[NATO]]\u2019s [[Kosovo Force]]. He is the grandson of Brigadier General Albert Bryant, Sr. is a recipient of the [[Congressional Gold Medal]] and a former [[Montford Point Marine Association|Montford Point Marine]] and Army Brigadier General Richard Saxton. He is also the nephew of [[Emmy Award|Emmy]]-winning writer and speaker [[Lori Bryant-Woolridge]].\n\nBryant graduated from [[Giessen American High School]] in [[Giessen]], [[Germany]] in 1994, commencing study at the [[University of Texas at Austin]], that same year.<ref name=\":0\" />  At Texas, he studied journalism and communication studies from 1994-1998, when an extended illness led to medical withdrawal prior to graduation. When professional demands later prevented a full-time return to Texas, Bryant completed a [[Bachelor of Science]] degree from [[New York (state)|New York]]\u2019s [[Excelsior College]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://alumnius.net/excelsior_college-8954-2#id11065057|title=Alumni US {{!}} Excelsior College, Albany, New York Area|website=alumnius.net|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Bryant earned two Master\u2019s degrees, a [[Master of Arts]] in Administration and a [[Master of Science]] in Organizational Development and Leadership, from the [[University of the Incarnate Word]] in [[San Antonio]], [[Texas]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://alumnius.net/university_of_the_in-9551-year-2015#id11065057|title=Alumni US {{!}} University of the Incarnate Word (2015)|website=alumnius.net|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref>\n\n== Journalism and broadcasting ==\nIn 1996, Bryant was serving as a [[radio news]] intern at [[Austin, Texas|Austin]] radio station [[KKMJ]] when the [[Olympic Bomber|Atlanta Olympic Bombing]] occurred.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Who was that voice?|last=Grieg|first=Jane|date=August 1996|work=Austin American-Statesman|access-date=|month=|year=}}</ref> His impromptu overnight coverage gathered attention from the public and [[Austin American-Statesman]] columnist Jane Grieg, leading to a full-time role consisting of on-air roles at KKMJ and named Program Director, with news and local programming responsibility, of its sister station, ABC Radio affiliate [[KJCE]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://benjaminbryant.net/clipbook/ARSNewsletter.pdf|title=Americans on the Rise|last=|first=|date=July 1996|work=ARS Newsletter|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=The JUICE changes its on-air fare|last=Herndon|first=John|date=October 1996|work=Austin American-Statesman|access-date=}}</ref> Bryant also hosted KJCE\u2019s weekly Sunday morning current affairs program.\n\nAfter leaving Austin and the radio industry, Bryant worked as a freelance journalist<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/78606345/Montgomery-Gazette-Coverage-of-Maryland-Regional-AIDS-Conference|title=Montgomery Gazette Coverage of Maryland Regional AIDS Conference|website=Scribd|language=en|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref> and columnist before focusing on public relations and crisis communications consulting for public and private sector clients, though in those capacities, he served as writer and editor of multiple public-facing government publications, including the ''Deepwater News'' and ''FHP&R: Force Health Protection & Readiness'' magazine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://issuu.com/thebzgroup/docs/fhprmag_fall2007|title=Force Health Protection & Readiness Magazine - Fall 2007|website=Issuu|language=en|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref> He returned to broadcasting as the host of the \u201cBZCast\u201d podcast in 2017, including an award-winning exploration of leaking and whistleblowing in the federal government,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thebzgroup.com/the-bz-cast-leaking-or-whistleblowing/|title=The BZ Cast \u2013 Leaking or Whistleblowing?|website=thebzgroup.com|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref> and in a more significant way in 2018 with the launch of non-profit media platform [http://www.thebzmp.com BZ/MP] and the debut of the \u201c[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VuMyz4eFW8I The Brink with Benjamin Bryant],\u201d a series of one-on-one interview specials focusing on [[Washington, D.C.|Washington D.C.]] notables, and its spin-off serialized investigative podcast, \u201c[https://thebzmp.podbean.com/ The Brink with Benjamin Bryant: INTERSECTIONS],\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thebzmp.com/bzmpradio20181213-brinkreturns/|title=THE BRINK Returns with \"Intersections\" in 2019 - BZ/MP Radio|date=2018-12-13|website=BZ/MP|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref> both of which have since received a number of awards and honors, including several for Bryant as producer and host. In 2018, Bryant also appeared in an award-winning, non-partisan public service announcement entitled \"The One Place Everyone is Equal.\"<ref>{{Citation|last=BZ/MP - The Bryant Zamberlan Media Project|title=The One Place Everyone is Equal: The Ballot Box|date=2019-01-23|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IjupfK9zKeI|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref>\n\n== Military and government ==\n\nBryant has served in a variety of communications roles for the military services, including as a speechwriter for Rear Admiral Patrick Stillman of the [[United States Coast Guard]], and communications advisor for the Hon. [[James I. Finley|James Finley]] and then as a speechwriter and communications advisor for several senior military leaders, and has worked on multiple high-profile roles on Presidential task forces and commissions, including the Pentagon\u2019s [[2009 Fort Hood shooting|Fort Hood Shooting Task Force]], \u201c[[Don't ask, don't tell|Don\u2019t Ask, Don\u2019t Tell\u201d Repeal Working Group]], and the Military Compensation and Retirement Modernization Commission, for which he served as the agency\u2019s final [[spokesperson]]. On multiple occasions, Bryant appeared as a guest on  the nightly news program [[America Tonight]], hosted by journalist [[Joie Chen]], speaking to military issues in the news,.<ref>{{Citation|title=America Tonight : ALJAZAM : September 17, 2013 4:00am-5:01am EDT|date=2013-09-17|url=http://archive.org/details/ALJAZAM_20130917_080000_America_Tonight|others=ALJAZAM|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=America Tonight : ALJAZAM : April 3, 2014 12:00am-1:01am EDT|date=2014-04-03|url=http://archive.org/details/ALJAZAM_20140403_040000_America_Tonight|others=ALJAZAM|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=America Tonight : ALJAZAM : April 4, 2014 4:00am-5:01am EDT|date=2014-04-04|url=http://archive.org/details/ALJAZAM_20140404_080000_America_Tonight|others=ALJAZAM|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref>\n\nBryant's work as a government consultant and contracted advisor also includes substantial efforts in the public health arena. Bryant worked as a communications advisor to the [[United States Department of Defense|DoD]] Force Health Protection and Readiness agency, serving as speechwriter to [[Deputy Assistant Secretary of Defense]] Ellen Embrey, and supervising a redesign and relaunch of the agency's globally-distributed ''FHP&R: Force Health Protection'' full-color print magazine. In 2011, Bryant led a team of Bryant Zamberlan Group researchers, analysts, and writers (including former acting [[Surgeon General of the United States Army]] [[Major general (United States)|Major General]] Gail Pollock) conducting a federally-funded assessment of community preparedness and the effectiveness of [[public health]] outreach and education regarding [[Influenza pandemic|pandemic influenza]] health risks in the [[Virginia Beach, Virginia|Virginia Beach]] area. Bryant also authored the team's final report.\n\n==== Task Forces and Commissions ====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Name\n!Leadership\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|2009-2010\n|[[2009 Fort Hood shooting|Department of Defense<br>Fort Hood Shooting Task Force]]\n|Hon. [[Togo D. West Jr.|Togo D. West, Jr.]],<br>Adm. [[Vern Clark]]\n|Managing Editor,<br>Writing and Admin Team Lead\n|\n|-\n|2010\n|US Air Force Fort Hood Task Force Follow-on\n|Sec. [[Michael B. Donley]]\n|Senior Writer,<br>Writing Team Lead\n|\n|-\n|2010\n|\"[[Don't ask, don't tell|Don't Ask, Don't Tell]]\" Comprehensive Review Working Group\n|Hon. [[Jeh Johnson]],\nGen. [[Carter Ham]]\n|Lead Editor,<br>Editorial and Production Lead\n|\n|-\n|2011\n|[[Virginia Department of Health]]/[[Virginia Beach, Virginia|VA Beach]]<br>[[Influenza pandemic|Pandemic Influenza]] Program Assessment\n|Benjamin Bryant\n|Executive Director,<br>Report Author\n|\n|-\n|2013-2016\n|Military Compensation and Retirement Modernization Commission\n|Hon. Al Maldon\n|Assoc. Director, Public Relations and Outreach {{small|(2015-2016)}},<br>Lead Writer and Editor and<br>Editorial and Production Lead {{small|(2013-2015)}}\n|\n|-\n|}\n\nIn 2011, news reports covered Bryant and Thomas Zamberlan's donation of their original editor's copies from several Presidential and DoD task forces to the [[Smithsonian Institution]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.macombdaily.com/news/work-of-sterling-heights-native-added-to-smithsonian/article_b0eb5ded-3191-5597-8138-327ec13c91f5.html|title=Work of Sterling Heights native added to Smithsonian|last=KASZUBSKI|first=DEBRA|website=Macomb Daily|language=en|access-date=2019-05-24}}</ref> That same year, the [[Dolph Briscoe Center for American History]] at Bryant's alma mater [[University of Texas at Austin]], announced the acquisition of Bryant's personal notes, papers, and recorded recollections related to his work on the historic Fort Hood investigation and \"Don't Ask, Don't Tell\" repeals and their intention to make them available to researchers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://legacy.lib.utexas.edu/taro/utcah/03175/03175-P.html|title=A Guide to the Benjamin Bryant Papers, 2010|website=legacy.lib.utexas.edu|access-date=2019-05-24}}</ref>\n\nSince 2010, Bryant has been an Auxiliarist in the [[United States Coast Guard Auxiliary]], including service as a Flotilla Staff Officer.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.linkedin.com/in/benbryant13|title=Benjamin Bryant|website=LinkedIn|access-date=March 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Arts ==\n\nIn addition to his news and documentary work, Bryant has done substantial work in the arts, including film, television, and visual arts.\n\n=== Film and Television ===\n[[File:Anacostia S5 Interior3.jpg|thumb|Benjamin Bryant with actress Marion Akpan on the set of [[Anacostia (web series)|Anacostia]] in 2017]]\nBryant began producing narrative television and film projects in 2016, first joining the Daytime Emmy-winning, six-time nominated, digital series ''[[Anacostia (web series)|Anacostia]]'', from creator Anthony Anderson at the start of its fifth season, as a supervising producer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://benjaminbryant.kinja.com/anacostia-showrunner-anthony-anderson-talks-tackling-ma-1792659968|title=ANACOSTIA's Anthony Anderson tackles male/male rape (and gentrification!) in season five, and feels the responsibilities of African American storytelling|last=Bryant|first=Benjamin|website=Benjamin Bryant|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref><ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm8616001/|title=Benjamin Bryant|website=IMDb|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref> Beginning with episode five, Bryant was named co-[[executive producer]] of the series, a role he continued in until September 2019.<ref name=\":12\" /><ref name=\":22\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/gp/video/detail/B07H5VP6TF/ref=atv_dp_season_select_atf/139-3312839-3468708|title=Amazon.com: Watch Anacostia {{!}} Prime Video|website=www.amazon.com|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref> He also occasionally recurred on the series in the role of news anchor \"James Vance,\" an homage to the late Washington D.C. news anchor [[Jim Vance]].<ref name=\":12\" />\n\nIn 2019, his company, the Bryant Zamberlan Group, partnered with Gemelli Films and writer-director Candice Cain to produce the \"Candy Cain\" series of holiday films,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.welovesoaps.net/2019/08/Candy-Cain-holiday-films.html|title='Candy Cain' Holiday Trio of Films Features Former Soap Stars Patrick Muldoon, Carrie Genzel, Terri Garber, Jennifer Bassey, Cynthia Gibb|last=Newcomb|first=Roger|language=en|access-date=2019-09-11}}</ref> completing work on the holiday romances ''Ivy & Mistletoe'', starring [[Cody Calafiore]], [[Carrie Genzel]], and [[Cynthia Gibb]]; Destination: Christmas, starring Calafiore, [[Clayton Snyder]], and [[Abigail Hawk]]; and ''Painting Christmas'', starring Calafiore, Genzel, [[Patrick Muldoon]], [[Frank Whaley]], [[Terri Garber]], and [[Jennifer Bassey]],<ref name=\":12\" /> with the Global Genesis Group handling distribution.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/news/ni62583210|title='Candy Cain' Holiday Trio of Films|last=|first=|date=|website=IMDb|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-11}}</ref> Bryant, who served as the supervising producer on the films, also makes a cameo appearance in each one.<ref name=\":12\"/> Bryant also served as an Associate Producer on Cain's ''Joy & Hope'' a western-themed romance co-starring [[Vivica A. Fox]].\n\nIn September 2019, Bryant and travel writer Olivia Taylor announced on their respective social media platforms that they would co-host an upcoming travel show for the 2019-2020 season, titled \"Journey's Beyond.\"<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/poop.love/posts/10214112602995280|title=I'm hosting a new travel show|last=|first=|date=|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-11}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/bzbenbryant/posts/2515270521893195|title=A little tease for you|last=Bryant|first=Benjamin|date=|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B2OMBilhy_0/|title=Benjamin Bryant on Instagram: \"All I can share for now, but watch this space for details on my newest adventure!\"|last=|first=|date=|website=Instagram|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-11}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2020, production in [[Las Vegas]], [[Nevada]] was paused on Bryant's sports mockumentary ''Aidy Kane'' due to the [[COVID-19]] pandemic.\n\n==== Film ====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|1996\n|''[[Courage Under Fire]]''\n|Soldier (uncredited)\n|<ref name=\":12\"/>\n|-\n|2019\n|''Ivy & Mistletoe''\n|Supervising Producer, ''Air Traveler'' (cameo)\n|<ref name=\":12\"/>\n|-\n|2019\n|''Destination: Christmas''\n|Supervising Producer, ''Airline Employee'' (cameo)\n|<ref name=\":12\"/>\n|-\n|2019\n|''Painting Christmas''\n|Supervising Producer, ''Waterbury Coach'' (cameo)\n|<ref name=\":12\"/>\n|-\n|2020\n|''Aidy Kane''\n|Director, \u201cPhineas Strong\u201d\n|<ref>{{Citation|title=Aidy Kane|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt10868884/|access-date=2019-09-11}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==== Television and Digital Streaming ====\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|2016-2019\n|''[[Anacostia (web series)|Anacostia]]''\n|co-Executive Producer, \u201cJames Vance\u201d\n|<ref name=\":12\"/><ref name=\":22\"/>\n|-\n|2018-2019\n|''The Brink with Benjamin Bryant''\n|Executive Producer, Host\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thebzmp.com/bzmptv20181201-bzmpdc-brinkspecial/|title=WATCH NOW: The Brink's BZ/MP D.C. interviews come to life!|date=2018-12-01|website=BZ/MP|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref>\n|-\n|2018\n|''Unraveling Knots: The Journey Begins''\n|Executive Producer, Host\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thebzmp.com/bzmptv20181231-knotsjourney/|title=WATCH NOW: Unraveling Knots: The Journey Begins - BZ/MP TV|date=2018-12-31|website=BZ/MP|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref>\n|-\n|2018\n|''BZ Explains! Welcome to the Show''\n|The Narrator (character)\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thebzmp.com/bzmptv20181231-openingcredits/|title=WATCH NOW: Welcome to the Show: TV's First Impressions - BZ/MP TV|date=2018-12-31|website=BZ/MP|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref>\n|-\n|-\n|2019\n|Journeys Beyond\n|Executive Producer, co-Host\n|<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":8\" />\n|}\n\n=== Painting and photography ===\n\nIn the 2010s, Bryant has also worked intermittently as professional artist, photographer, and painter, signing his work as \"Ben Bryant.<nowiki>''</nowiki> His pieces featured and sold through the [[Saatchi Gallery]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.saatchiart.com/benjaminbryant|title=Benjamin Bryant|website=Saatchi Art|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref> In 2018, a whimsical portrait Bryant painted in hours, was featured on the sixth season premiere of \"Anacostia\" (in a roadside shrine honoring a child lost to gun violence).<ref>{{Citation|last=ANACOSTIASERIES|title=ANACOSTIA Season 6 Episode 1 \"Aftermath\"|date=2018-12-30|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Y6jDScxVREk|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref> Shortly after, it became the first of his paintings to sell for more than $1,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.saatchiart.com/art/Painting-Taty-featured-on-the-Emmy-winning-series-Anacostia/1131628/4636336/view|title=Taty (featured on the Emmy-winning series \"Anacostia\") Painting|website=Saatchi Art|language=en|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref> He is also an artistic, commercial, and editorial photographer. The posters for the films ''Destination: Christmas'' and ''Painting Christmas'', which Bryant produced, feature his photography.\n\n== Business ==\n\nSince 2010, Bryant has served as the Managing Partner of the Bryant Zamberlan Group of companies, which include a global communications consultancy and BZ/MP, a non-profit news and media endeavor. In this role, Bryant holds multiple certifications, and has advised and trained senior leaders in the United States Government and international business.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Awards, Honors, and Nominations ==\nBryant has received numerous industry honors and nominations for his work as a journalist, broadcaster, and producer, beginning with two Paul R. Ellis awards from the American Heart Association of Texas in 1996 for writing and producing content to educate the Austin, TX community regarding increased heart disease and stroke risks in minority communities at radio station [[KJCE]].\n\nSince 1999, he has been honored with Communicator, MarCom, Hermes Creative, W3, Davey, AVA, and Silver Inkwell awards for various writing, multimedia, video, and other projects.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://enter.avaawards.com/|title=AVA Digital Awards|website=enter.avaawards.com|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.communicatorawards.com/winners/gallery/|title=Communicator Awards {{!}} Award of Excellence Winners Gallery|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.daveyawards.com/winners/winners/|title=Davey Awards {{!}} Winners|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://enter.hermesawards.com/|title=Hermes Creative Awards|website=enter.hermesawards.com|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref>\n\nAs co-executive producer of the six-time [[Emmy Award|Emmy]] nominated [[Anacostia (web series)|Anacostia]], Bryant received a 2018 [[Indie Series Awards|Indie Series Award]] nomination, Hermes Creative Award, Telly Award, and two consecutive Best Drama Series honors at the Rome Web Awards.\n\nOther notable honors include a 2010 Platinum MarCom \"Special Category\" Award for his work as the Managing Editor of the report of the Fort Hood Task Force, 2012 Davey Award for his appearances on ''America Tonight'', 2019 Communicator Award of Distinction for \"The Brink with Benjamin Bryant\" interview specials; and multiple Platinum AVA and Hermes Creative Awards for \"The Brink with Benjamin Bryant: INTERSECTIONS\" podcast (including honors for writing, hosting, and production).<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIn a year-end feature dedicated to the people and stories who made the year notable, Bryant was named by the Austin American-Statesman as one of its most memorable people in 1996.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Looking Back at the People Who Made 1996 Memorable: 'Familiar Voice'|last=Grieg|first=Jane|date=January 2, 1997|work=Austin American-Statesman|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n\nBryant currently lives in the Washington, D.C. metro area.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n*[[imdbname:8616001|''Benjamin Bryant (II)'' IMDb.com]]\n*{{cite news|url=http://benjaminbryant.net/clipbook/robpatterson0497.html|title=Some Questions: Radio's Benjamin Bryant|last=Patterson|first=Robert|date=1997-04-10|work=[[Austin American-Statesman]]|accessdate=2019-04-13|publisher=[[Cox Media Group]]}}\n* {{cite news|url=http://benjaminbryant.net/clipbook/johnherndon0197.html|title=Radio: Tough Work if You Can Get It|last=Herndon|first=John|date=1997-01-02|work=[[Austin American-Statesman]]|accessdate=2019-04-13|publisher=[[Cox Media Group]]}}\n*[http://www.thebzgroup.com/ ''