-five-most-ridiculous-ideas-from-goops-health-conference/|archive-date=2018-02-02}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=NW2>{{Cite news|last=Watling|first=Eve|url=https://www.newsweek.com/vaccines-anti-vaxxers-reasons-1340494|title=Why do some people believe vaccines are dangerous?|date=2019-02-25|work=Newsweek|access-date=2020-03-28|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190602015324/https://www.newsweek.com/vaccines-anti-vaxxers-reasons-1340494|archive-date=2019-06-02}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=coffee>{{cite news |last1=Gunter |first1=Jen |title=Don\u2019t listen to Gwyneth Paltrow: keep your coffee well away from your rectum {{!}} Jen Gunter |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2018/jan/09/gwyneth-paltrow-goop-coffee-enema-colonic-irrigation |accessdate=29 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=9 January 2018 }}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brogan, Kelly}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American health activists]]\n[[Category:Anti-vaccination activists]]\n[[Category:Pseudoscientific diet advocates]]\n[[Category:Alternative medicine activists]]\n[[Category:HIV/AIDS denialists]]\n[[Category:American conspiracy theorists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description | American psychiatrist and alternative medicine practitioner}}\n{{Use American English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Kelly Brogan\n| image = Kelly Brogan.png\n| imagesize = 180px\n| alt = Profile photo of Kelly Brogan\n| caption = Kelly Brogan in 2019\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| othername = \n| occupation = Psychiatrist and alternative medicine practitioner\n| years_active = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = ''A Mind of Your Own: The Truth About Depression and How Women Can Heal Their Bodies to Reclaim Their Lives''\n| residence = \n| spouse = \n| domesticpartner = \n| website = {{URL|kellybroganmd.com}} \n}}\n{{Alternative medical systems|fringe}}\n\n'''Kelly Brogan''' is an American [[psychiatrist]], author of books on [[alternative medicine]] and a promoter of discredited medical theories. \n\n==Background and credentials==\n\nBrogan graduated from [[Weill Cornell Medicine|Cornell University Medical College]] in Psychiatry, and has a B.S. in Systems Neuroscience from [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]].{{R|Goop1}} She uses the title of \"holistic psychiatrist\".{{R|Ind1}}\n\n[[Quackery|Medical fraud]] researcher Peter Heimlich points out Brogan appears to have failed to maintain certification with the [[American Board of Psychiatry and Neurology]], according to the association's database. She removed her claim of being certified in psychiatry and [[psychosomatic medicine]] from her website after Heimlich's research was made public.{{R|Beast1}}\n\nBrogan wrote about health on [[Gwyneth Paltrow]]'s [[Goop (company)|Goop]] retail website and was featured on expert panels at several Goop events.{{R|Ind1}}{{R|Forb1}}{{R|Jez1}}{{R|McL1}}\n\n==Alternative medicine controversies==\n\nBrogan promotes the belief that human diseases are caused not by [[Pathogen|infectious agents]], but rather by psychological factors. She mocks the well-established notion of \"little invisible pathogens, you know, that randomly jump around from person to person\".{{R|Ind1}}{{R|Beast1}}{{R|Forb1}}{{R|ES1}}\n\nIn March 2020, during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], Brogan indicated at length that, in her opinion, the virus may not exist. According to her, it's rather the fear of a virus that makes people sick and die. She referred her followers to the [[Pseudoscience|pseudoscientific]] claims of [[Joseph Mercola]] and [[Ryke Geerd Hamer]] on the topic. [[Twitter]], [[Facebook]], [[Vimeo]] and [[Instagram]] removed Brogan's videos, presumably as part of their efforts to limit the spread of misinformation during the epidemic, a move Brogan described as \"censorship\".{{R|Ind1}}{{R|Beast1}}{{R|ES1}}{{R|LA1}}\n\nBrogan's claims about the cause of diseases, as have Hamer's and Mercola's, have been debunked by medical experts as dangerous misconceptions.{{R|Beast1}}\n\nOn that occasion and others prior, she accused the government of being controlled by pro-vaccination \"elites\" with a sinister agenda. She suggested the pandemic was a ploy by the United States government to force vaccination on people and usher in totalitarian measures.{{R|Ind1}}{{R|Beast1}}{{R|ES1}} Investigator [[Benjamin Radford]] attributes Brogan's theories to a wider phenomenon of self-styled populist health experts inciting people to reject science and embrace their own theories.{{R|Beast1}}\n\nIn a similar vein, Brogan [[HIV/AIDS denialism|attributed the death of AIDS patients not to HIV]], but to treatments meant to fight it. Even though the link between HIV and AIDS is clearly established by medical research, she calls it an \"assumption\". She also defended the disproven belief that intestinal bacteria cause depression; Brogan invites people to stop taking [[antidepressant]]s and use the techniques and products from her website instead.{{R|Forb1}}{{R|Jez1}}{{R|McL1}}{{R|NW1}}{{R|SBM1}} Through her website, Brogan offers a subscription-only \"lifestyle medicine\" community space and access to self-improvement training resources.{{R|Brog1}}\n\nShe also promotes many of the usual [[Vaccine hesitancy|erroneous claims against vaccines]], notably that the immunity gained from surviving an infectious disease is superior to the one generated by being vaccinated. She also denies [[polio]] was eradicated by vaccination.{{R|Forb1}}{{R|Jez1}}{{R|ES1}}{{R|SBM1}}{{R|NW2}}\n\nDespite [[Coffee enema|coffee enemas]] being long discredited as medical procedures, Brogan promotes them for depression.{{R|McL1}}{{R|coffee}}\n\n==Personal life==\n\nBrogan lives in Florida{{R|Beast1}} and has two children.{{R|Goop1}}\n\n==Books==\n\n* {{Cite book|last=Brogan|first=Kelly|title=Own Your Self: The Surprising Path beyond Depression, Anxiety, and Fatigue to Reclaiming Your Authenticity, Vitality, and Freedom|publisher=Hay House|year=2019|isbn=978-1401956820|location=|pages=352}}{{R|Amaz3}}\n\n* {{Cite book|last=Brogan|first=Kelly|title=A Mind of Your Own: The Truth About Depression and How Women Can Heal Their Bodies to Reclaim Their Lives|publisher=Harper Wave|year=2016|isbn=978-0062405579|location=|page=|pages=352}}{{R|Amaz1}} On the [[The New York Times Best Seller list|New York Times' list of best-selling books]].{{R|Ind1}} \n\n* (as editor) {{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Integrative Therapies for Depression: Redefining Models for Assessment, Treatment and Prevention|last2=|publisher=CRC Press|year=2015|isbn=978-1498702294|editor-last=Greenblatt|editor-first=James|editor-last2=Brogan|editor-first2=Kelly|location=|pages=531}}{{R|Amaz2}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=Ind1>{{Cite news|last=Ritschel|first=Chelsea|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/goop-coronavirus-kelly-brogan-expert-contributor-md-deaths-covid-19-a9421476.html|title=Goop expert says coronavirus doesn't exist: 'There is potentially no such thing'|date=2020-03-25|work=The Independant|access-date=2020-03-28|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328122701/https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/goop-coronavirus-kelly-brogan-expert-contributor-md-deaths-covid-19-a9421476.html?fbclid=IwAR01Xw5CzjFkReWZz81WXpdg4BXDi5Kau9KBq2j_hA_gQ1lxgPSRdzn2N7Y|archive-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Beast1>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/the-gwyneth-paltrow-approved-goop-doctor-pushing-wacky-coronavirus-conspiracies|title=The Gwyneth Paltrow-Approved Doctor Pushing Wacky Coronavirus Conspiracies|last=Jones|first=Sterling|date=2020-03-25|website=The Daily Beast|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328131922/https://www.thedailybeast.com/the-gwyneth-paltrow-approved-goop-doctor-pushing-wacky-coronavirus-conspiracie