oup=\"nb\"}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/coronavirus-covid-19/ Coronavirus (COVID-19) on the NHS website]\n* [https://www.gov.uk/coronavirus Coronavirus (COVID-19): UK government information ]\n* [https://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2020/129/contents/made The Health Protection (Coronavirus) Regulations 2020]. Legislation.gov.uk\n* [https://www.publichealth.hscni.net/publications/advice-covid-19-coronavirus Public Health Agency] \u2013 Advice on COVID-19 (coronavirus)\n* [https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/country/uk/ Worldometer UK Statistics] \u2013 Worldometer graphs and statistics for the UK\n* [https://coronavirus-global.com/uk Coronavirus United Kingdom updates and news]. United Kingdom in Coronavirus Global international portal. Available in English, French, Spanish and more.\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|short=yes}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom}}\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|United Kingdom|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom| ]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:January 2020 events in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:February 2020 events in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe|United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "GunnisonMarmot", "label": "safe", "comment": "minor a few articles, commas, and spaces.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_the_United_Kingdom"}
{"title_page": "Zoran \u010cutura", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{BLP sources|date=August 2010}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name         = Zoran \u010cutura\n| image        = \n| image_size   = \n| caption      = \n| position     = \n| height_m     = 2.02\n| weight_kg    = \n| league       = \n| team         = \n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1962|3|12}}\n| birth_place  = [[Zagreb]], [[SR Croatia]], [[SFR Yugoslavia]]\n| nationality  = Croatian\n| career_start = 1978\n| career_end   = 1995\n| career_position = [[Small forward]] / [[Power forward (basketball)|Power forward]]\n| years1       = 1978\u20131981\n| team1        = [[KK Zrinjevac|Industromonta\u017ea / Monting]]\n| years2       = 1981\u20131993\n| team2        = [[KK Cibona|Cibona]]\n| years3       = 1993\u20131995\n| team3        = [[KK Split|Croatia Osiguranje]]\n| highlights   = \n* 2\u00d7 [[EuroLeague]] champion ([[1984\u201385 FIBA European Champions Cup|1985]], [[1985\u201386 FIBA European Champions Cup|1986]])\n* 2\u00d7 [[Saporta Cup]] champion ([[1981\u201382 FIBA European Cup Winners' Cup|1982]], [[1986\u201387 FIBA European Cup Winners' Cup|1987]])\n* 3\u00d7 [[Yugoslav First Basketball League|Yugoslav League]] champion ([[1981\u201382 Yugoslav First Basketball League|1982]], [[1983\u201384 Yugoslav First Basketball League|1984]], [[1984\u201385 Yugoslav First Basketball League|1985]])\n* [[A-1 Liga|Croatian League]] champion (1992)\n* 5\u00d7 [[Yugoslav Basketball Cup|Yugoslav Cup]] winner (1982, 1983, 1985, 1986, 1988)\n* [[Kre\u0161imir \u0106osi\u0107 Cup|Croatian Cup]] winner (1994)\n| medal_templates  =\n{{MedalCountry|{{bk|YUG}}}}\n{{MedalOlympic}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[1988 Summer Olympics|1988 Seoul]]|[[Basketball at the 1988 Summer Olympics|Team]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA World Championship]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1990 FIBA World Championship|1990 Argentina]]|}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[1986 FIBA World Championship|1986 Spain]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[EuroBasket]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[EuroBasket 1989|1989 Yugoslavia]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship|European Championship for Juniors]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[1980 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship|1980 Yugoslavia]]|[[Yugoslavia men's national under-18 basketball team|Team]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA Europe Under-16 Championship|European Championship for Cadets]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1979 FIBA Europe Under-16 Championship|1979 Syria]]|[[Yugoslavia men's national under-16 basketball team|Team]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Zoran \u010cutura''' (born 12 March 1962 in [[Zagreb]]) is a former Croatian basketball player. After ending his professional basketball career he started working as a [[sports journalist]] and [[columnist]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Zoran \u010cutura \u2013 biblija ko\u0161arke i novinarstva|url=https://www.vice.com/rs/article/wn5mxw/zoran-cutura-biblija-kosarke-i-novinarstva|accessdate=November 30, 2018|work=vice.com|date=August 27, 2015|language=Serbian}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n\n\u010cutura started playing basketball in his hometown [[Zagreb]]. His first club was the second division club [[KK Zrinjevac|Industromonta\u017ea]] where he spent three years. In 1981 he joined the Zagreb powerhouse [[KK Cibona|Cibona]] where [[Mirko Novosel]] was starting to build the future European champion team with players like the veteran [[Kre\u0161imir \u0106osi\u0107]], [[Aleksandar Petrovi\u0107 (basketball)|Aleksandar Petrovi\u0107]], [[Dra\u017een Petrovi\u0107]], [[Andro Knego]], [[Ivo Naki\u0107]] and [[Branko Vuki\u010devi\u0107]]. This team won two back-to-back [[EuroLeague|European Champions Cup]]s in [[1984\u201385 FIBA European Champions Cup|1985]] and [[1985\u201386 FIBA European Champions Cup|1986]].<ref name=\"euroleague\"/>\n\nIn his first season in Cibona (1981\u201382), \u010cutura won a triple crown: the [[Yugoslav Basketball Cup|Yugoslav Cup]] by defeating [[KK Bosna Royal|Bosna]] in the final, the [[1981\u201382 Yugoslav First Basketball League|Yugoslav League]] by winning in the first play-off organized by the [[Basketball Federation of Yugoslavia]] and the [[1981\u201382 FIBA European Cup Winners' Cup|European Cup Winners' Cup]] by defeating [[Real Madrid Baloncesto|Real Madrid]] in the final. He won another [[Yugoslav Basketball Cup|Yugoslav Cup]] in 1983 and another [[1983\u201384 Yugoslav First Basketball League|Yugoslav League]] trophy in 1984. The second triple crown came in 1985, this time including the [[1984\u201385 FIBA European Champions Cup|European champion]] title. For their second European trophy Cibona defeated [[Real Madrid Baloncesto|Real Madrid]] in the [[1985 FIBA European Champions Cup Final|final]] again with \u010cutura scoring 16 points.\n\n\u010cutura won his second [[EuroLeague|European champion]] title in 1986 participating with 16 points in the [[1986 FIBA European Champions Cup Final|final victory]] against [[\u017dalgiris (basketball club)|\u017dalgiris]].\n\n\u010cutura won two more [[Yugoslav Basketball Cup|Yugoslav Cup]]s in 1986 and 1988 as well as another [[European Cup Winners' Cup]] in [[1986\u201387 FIBA European Cup Winners' Cup|1987]]. In the final victory against [[U.S. Victoria Libertas Pallacanestro|Scavolini Pesaro]] he scored six points. His last trophy with [[KK Cibona|Cibona]] was the [[A-1 Liga|Croatian League]] in 1992.\n\nIn 1993, after 12 seasons spent in [[KK Cibona|Cibona]], \u010cutura moved to [[KK Split|Split]] where he spent two seasons before retiring. With Split he won his last trophy\u2014the [[Kre\u0161imir \u0106osi\u0107 Cup|Croatian Cup]] in 1994.\n\n==National team career==\n\n\u010cutura played with the [[Yugoslavia national basketball team]] at the [[1979 FIBA Europe Under-16 Championship|1979 European Championship for Cadets]] where his team took gold. He was the team's leading scorer with a 23.9 points average. \u010cutura's second major tournament was the first [[1979 FIBA Under-19 World Championship|World Under-19 Championship]], held the same year in Brazil where Yugoslavia finished fourth. His team mates included [[\u017deljko Obradovi\u0107]], [[Goran Grbovi\u0107]] and [[Zoran Radovi\u0107]]. He was the team's top scorer with 16.3 ppg. He was once again the top scorer (22.8 p) of his team (even though still playing for a second division club) at the [[1980 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship|1980 European Championship for Juniors]] where he won silver.<ref name=\"euroleague\"/>\n\n\u010cutura's first major senior tournament was the [[1985 EuroBasket]] where Yugoslavia took seventh place.\n\n\u010cutura won his first senior medal at the [[1986 FIBA World Championship|1986 World Championship]] where he played in a talent-packed team alongside [[Dra\u017een Petrovi\u0107]], [[Aleksandar Petrovi\u0107 (basketball)|Aleksandar Petrovi\u0107]], [[Dra\u017een Dalipagi\u0107]], [[Vlade Divac]], [[Danko Cvjeti\u0107anin]] and others. Yugoslavia took bronze with \u010cutura contributing 10.3 ppg. \n \nHead coach [[Kre\u0161imir \u0106osi\u0107]] did not call-up \u010cutura for the [[1987 EuroBasket]], but \u010cutura was back on the team at the [[Basketball at the 1988 Summer Olympics|1988 Summer Olympics]] under coach [[Du\u0161an Ivkovi\u0107]]. Yugoslavia took silver with \u010cutura making 8.2 ppg.<ref>{{cite Sports-Reference |title=Zoran \u010cutura |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/cu/zoran-cutura-1.html |accessdate=28 January 2016}}</ref> At the [[1989 Eurobasket]] played in front of his hometown crowd \u010cutura (5.0 ppg) along with [[Dra\u017een Petrovi\u0107]], [[Dino Ra\u0111a]], [[\u017darko Paspalj]], [[Vlade Divac]], [[Predrag Danilovi\u0107]], [[Toni Kuko\u010d]], [[Jure Zdovc]] and others took gold.<ref name=\"euroleague\">{{cite news|title=Zoran Cutura, a great from the shadows|url=http://www.euroleague.net/news/voices/2014-2015/vladimir-stankovic/i/144242/zoran-cutura-a-great-from-the-shadows|accessdate=November 30, 2018|work=euroleague.net|date=November 9, 2014}}</ref>\n\n\u010cutura's last major tournament was the [[1990 FIBA World Championship|1990 World Championship]] where Yugoslavia were crowned champions. \u010cutura averaged 4.8 ppg. After the breakup of [[SFR Yugoslavia|Yugoslavia]], \u010cutura never made a major tournament squad for the [[Croatia national basketball team]].\n\n==After basketball==\n\nAfter his professional basketball career \u010cutura started working as a [[sports journalist]] and [[columnist]]. In 2008 he won a prize for the best Croatian sports journalist while writing for [[Jutarnji list]].<ref>{{cite news|title='Nagrada mi je poticaj da vas i dalje nerviram'|url=https://www.jutarnji.hr/arhiva/nagrada-mi-je-poticaj-da-vas-i-dalje-nerviram/3868326/|accessdate=November 30, 2018|work=jutarnji.hr|date=February 18, 2008|language=Croatian}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\n\u010cutura is married to Gordana Gojni\u0107-\u010cutura, a former [[Croatia women's national volleyball team]] player.<ref>{{cite news|title=HZSN: Zoran \u010cutura sportski novinar godine|url=http://www.poslovni.hr/hrvatska/hzsn-zoran-cutura-sportski-novinar-godine-70851|accessdate=November 30, 2018|work=poslovni.hr|date=February 19, 2008|language=Croatian}}</ref>\n\nHe is the father of Tomislav, a former basketball player at [[Lycoming College]] in Pennsylvania and [[:fr:Hana \u010cutura|Hana]], a professional volleyball player,<ref>{{cite news|title=Odbile smo o\u010deve i ko\u0161arku i, kao mame, posvetile se odbojci|url=http://arhiva.nacional.hr/clanak/13452/odbile-smo-oceve-i-kosarku-i-kao-mame-posvetile-se-odbojci|accessdate=November 30, 2018|work=arhiva.nacional.hr|date=May 6, 2003|language=Croatian}}</ref> occasional [[Croatia women's national volleyball team]] player and former student of the [[University of California, Berkeley]]. While she studied she played for the Golden Bear volleyball team that was a semifinalist at the 2007 NCAA Division I Women's Volleyball Tournament Final Four, as well as being the 2009 Pac-10 Player of the Year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://calbears.cstv.com/sports/w-volley/mtt/cutura_hana00.html |title=Player Bio: Hana Cutura |website=calbears.cstv.com |accessdate=27 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080914203056/http://calbears.cstv.com/sports/w-volley/mtt/cutura_hana00.html |archivedate=14 September 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IOC profile|zoran-cutura|Zoran Cutura}}\n*[http://www.fiba.basketball/pages/eng/fa/player/p/pid/7913/pid2/7324/sid/2302/tid/390/tid2/2792/_/1979_European_Championship_for_Cadets_Final_Round/index.html FIBA Profile]\n{{KK Cibona 1981\u201382 FIBA European Cup Winner's Cup Champions}}\n{{KK Cibona 1984-85 Euroleague champions}}\n{{KK Cibona 1985-86 Euroleague champions}}\n{{KK Cibona 1986\u201387 FIBA European Cup Winner's Cup Champions}}\n{{Yugoslavia Squad 1986 FIBA World Championship}}\n{{Footer 1988 Olympic Silver Medalists Basketball Men}}\n{{Yugoslavia Squad EuroBasket 1989}}\n{{Yugoslavia Squad 1990 FIBA World Championship}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cutura, Zoran}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Basketball players at the 1988 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Croatian men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:FIBA World Championship-winning players]]\n[[Category:Forwards (basketball)]]\n[[Category:KK Split players]]\n[[Category:KK Cibona players]]\n[[Category:KK Zrinjevac players]]\n[[Category:Olympic basketball players of Yugoslavia]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in basketball]]\n[[Category:Olympic silver medalists for Yugoslavia]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Zagreb]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:1986 FIBA World Championship players]]\n[[Category:1990 FIBA World Championship players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{BLP sources|date=August 2010}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name         = Zoran \u010cutura\n| image        = \n| image_size   = \n| caption      = \n| position     = \n| height_m     = 2.02\n| weight_kg    = \n| league       = \n| team         = \n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1962|3|12}}\n| birth_place  = [[Zagreb]], [[SR Croatia]], [[SFR Yugoslavia]]\n| nationality  = Croatian\n| career_start = 1978\n| career_end   = 1995\n| career_position = [[Small forward]] / [[Power forward (basketball)|Power forward]]\n| years1       = 1978\u20131981\n| team1        = [[KK Zrinjevac|Industromonta\u017ea / Monting]]\n| years2       = 1981\u20131993\n| team2        = [[KK Cibona|Cibona]]\n| years3       = 1993\u20131995\n| team3        = [[KK Split|Croatia Osiguranje]]\n| highlights   = \n* 2\u00d7 [[EuroLeague]] champion ([[1984\u201385 FIBA European Champions Cup|1985]], [[1985\u201386 FIBA European Champions Cup|1986]])\n* 2\u00d7 [[Saporta Cup]] champion ([[1981\u201382 FIBA European Cup Winners' Cup|1982]], [[1986\u201387 FIBA European Cup Winners' Cup|1987]])\n* 3\u00d7 [[Yugoslav First Basketball League|Yugoslav League]] champion ([[1981\u201382 Yugoslav First Basketball League|1982]], [[1983\u201384 Yugoslav First Basketball League|1984]], [[1984\u201385 Yugoslav First Basketball League|1985]])\n* [[A-1 Liga|Croatian League]] champion (1992)\n* 5\u00d7 [[Yugoslav Basketball Cup|Yugoslav Cup]] winner (1982, 1983, 1985, 1986, 1988)\n* [[Kre\u0161imir \u0106osi\u0107 Cup|Croatian Cup]] winner (1994)\n| medal_templates  =\n{{MedalCountry|{{bk|YUG}}}}\n{{MedalOlympic}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[1988 Summer Olympics|1988 Seoul]]|[[Basketball at the 1988 Summer Olympics|Team]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA World Championship]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1990 FIBA World Championship|1990 Argentina]]|}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[1986 FIBA World Championship|1986 Spain]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[EuroBasket]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[EuroBasket 1989|1989 Yugoslavia]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship|European Championship for Juniors]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[1980 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship|1980 Yugoslavia]]|[[Yugoslavia men's national under-18 basketball team|Team]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA Europe Under-16 Championship|European Championship for Cadets]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1979 FIBA Europe Under-16 Championship|1979 Syria]]|[[Yugoslavia men's national under-16 basketball team|Team]]}}\n}}\n'''Zoran \u010cutura''' (born 12 March 1962 in [[Zagreb]]) is a former Croatian basketball player. After ending his professional basketball career he started working as a [[sports journalist]] and [[columnist]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Zoran \u010cutura \u2013 biblija ko\u0161arke i novinarstva|url=https://www.vice.com/rs/article/wn5mxw/zoran-cutura-biblija-kosarke-i-novinarstva|accessdate=November 30, 2018|work=vice.com|date=August 27, 2015|language=Serbian}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n\n\u010cutura started playing basketball in his hometown [[Zagreb]]. His first club was the second division club [[KK Zrinjevac|Industromonta\u017ea]] where he spent three years. In 1981 he joined the Zagreb powerhouse [[KK Cibona|Cibona]] where [[Mirko Novosel]] was starting to build the future European champion team with players like the veteran [[Kre\u0161imir \u0106osi\u0107]], [[Aleksandar Petrovi\u0107 (basketball)|Aleksandar Petrovi\u0107]], [[Dra\u017een Petrovi\u0107]], [[Andro Knego]], [[Ivo Naki\u0107]] and [[Branko Vuki\u010devi\u0107]]. This team won two back-to-back [[EuroLeague|European Champions Cup]]s in [[1984\u201385 FIBA European Champions Cup|1985]] and [[1985\u201386 FIBA European Champions Cup|1986]].<ref name=\"euroleague\"/>\n\nIn his first season in Cibona (1981\u201382), \u010cutura won a triple crown: the [[Yugoslav Basketball Cup|Yugoslav Cup]] by defeating [[KK Bosna Royal|Bosna]] in the final, the [[1981\u201382 Yugoslav First Basketball League|Yugoslav League]] by winning in the first play-off organized by the [[Basketball Federation of Yugoslavia]] and the [[1981\u201382 FIBA European Cup Winners' Cup|European Cup Winners' Cup]] by defeating [[Real Madrid Baloncesto|Real Madrid]] in the final. He won another [[Yugoslav Basketball Cup|Yugoslav Cup]] in 1983 and another [[1983\u201384 Yugoslav First Basketball League|Yugoslav League]] trophy in 1984. The second triple crown came in 1985, this time including the [[1984\u201385 FIBA European Champions Cup|European champion]] title. For their second European trophy Cibona defeated [[Real Madrid Baloncesto|Real Madrid]] in the [[1985 FIBA European Champions Cup Final|final]] again with \u010cutura scoring 16 points.\n\n\u010cutura won his second [[EuroLeague|European champion]] title in 1986 participating with 16 points in the [[1986 FIBA European Champions Cup Final|final victory]] against [[\u017dalgiris (basketball club)|\u017dalgiris]].\n\n\u010cutura won two more [[Yugoslav Basketball Cup|Yugoslav Cup]]s in 1986 and 1988 as well as another [[European Cup Winners' Cup]] in [[1986\u201387 FIBA European Cup Winners' Cup|1987]]. In the final victory against [[U.S. Victoria Libertas Pallacanestro|Scavolini Pesaro]] he scored six points. His last trophy with [[KK Cibona|Cibona]] was the [[A-1 Liga|Croatian League]] in 1992.\n\nIn 1993, after 12 seasons spent in [[KK Cibona|Cibona]], \u010cutura moved to [[KK Split|Split]] where he spent two seasons before retiring. With Split he won his last trophy\u2014the [[Kre\u0161imir \u0106osi\u0107 Cup|Croatian Cup]] in 1994.\n\n==National team career==\n\n\u010cutura played with the [[Yugoslavia national basketball team]] at the [[1979 FIBA Europe Under-16 Championship|1979 European Championship for Cadets]] where his team took gold. He was the team's leading scorer with a 23.9 points average. \u010cutura's second major tournament was the first [[1979 FIBA Under-19 World Championship|World  Under-19 Championship]], held the same year in Brazil where Yugoslavia finished fourth. His team mates included [[\u017deljko Obradovi\u0107]], [[Goran Grbovi\u0107]] and [[Zoran Radovi\u0107]]. He was the team's top scorer with 16.3 ppg. He was once again the top scorer (22.8 p) of his team (even though still playing for a second division club) at the [[1980 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship|1980 European Championship for Juniors]] where he won silver.<ref name=\"euroleague\"/>\n\n\u010cutura's first major senior tournament was the [[1985 EuroBasket]] where Yugoslavia took seventh place.\n\n\u010cutura won his first senior medal at the [[1986 FIBA World Championship|1986 World Championship]] where he played in a talent-packed team alongside [[Dra\u017een Petrovi\u0107]], [[Aleksandar Petrovi\u0107 (basketball)|Aleksandar Petrovi\u0107]], [[Dra\u017een Dalipagi\u0107]], [[Vlade Divac]], [[Danko Cvjeti\u0107anin]] and others. Yugoslavia took bronze with \u010cutura contributing 10.3 ppg. \n \nHead coach [[Kre\u0161imir \u0106osi\u0107]] did not call-up \u010cutura for the [[1987 EuroBasket]], but \u010cutura was back on the team at the [[Basketball at the 1988 Summer Olympics|1988 Summer Olympics]] under coach [[Du\u0161an Ivkovi\u0107]]. Yugoslavia took silver with \u010cutura making 8.2 ppg.<ref>{{cite Sports-Reference |title=Zoran \u010cutura |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/cu/zoran-cutura-1.html |accessdate=28 January 2016}}</ref> At the [[1989 Eurobasket]] played in front of his hometown crowd \u010cutura (5.0 ppg) along with [[Dra\u017een Petrovi\u0107]], [[Dino Ra\u0111a]], [[\u017darko Paspalj]], [[Vlade Divac]], [[Predrag Danilovi\u0107]], [[Toni Kuko\u010d]], [[Jure Zdovc]] and others took gold.<ref name=\"euroleague\">{{cite news|title=Zoran Cutura, a great from the shadows|url=http://www.euroleague.net/news/voices/2014-2015/vladimir-stankovic/i/144242/zoran-cutura-a-great-from-the-shadows|accessdate=November 30, 2018|work=euroleague.net|date=November 9, 2014}}</ref>\n\n\u010cutura's last major tournament was the [[1990 FIBA World Championship|1990 World Championship]] where Yugoslavia were crowned champions. \u010cutura averaged 4.8 ppg. After the breakup of [[SFR Yugoslavia|Yugoslavia]], \u010cutura never made a major tournament squad for the [[Croatia national basketball team]].\n\n==After basketball==\n\nAfter his professional basketball career \u010cutura started working as a [[sports journalist]] and [[columnist]]. In 2008 he won a prize for the best Croatian sports journalist while writing for [[Jutarnji list]].<ref>{{cite news|title='Nagrada mi je poticaj da vas i dalje nerviram'|url=https://www.jutarnji.hr/arhiva/nagrada-mi-je-poticaj-da-vas-i-dalje-nerviram/3868326/|accessdate=November 30, 2018|work=jutarnji.hr|date=February 18, 2008|language=Croatian}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\n\u010cutura is married to Gordana Gojni\u0107-\u010cutura, a former [[Croatia women's national volleyball team]] player.<ref>{{cite news|title=HZSN: Zoran \u010cutura sportski novinar godine|url=http://www.poslovni.hr/hrvatska/hzsn-zoran-cutura-sportski-novinar-godine-70851|accessdate=November 30, 2018|work=poslovni.hr|date=February 19, 2008|language=Croatian}}</ref>\n\nHe is the father of Tomislav, a former basketball player at [[Lycoming College]] in Pennsylvania and [[:fr:Hana \u010cutura|Hana]], a professional volleyball player,<ref>{{cite news|title=Odbile smo o\u010deve i ko\u0161arku i, kao mame, posvetile se odbojci|url=http://arhiva.nacional.hr/clanak/13452/odbile-smo-oceve-i-kosarku-i-kao-mame-posvetile-se-odbojci|accessdate=November 30, 2018|work=arhiva.nacional.hr|date=May 6, 2003|language=Croatian}}</ref> occasional [[Croatia women's national volleyball team]] player and former student of the [[University of California, Berkeley]]. While she studied she played for the Golden Bear volleyball team that was a semifinalist at the 2007 NCAA Division I Women's Volleyball Tournament Final Four, as well as being the 2009 Pac-10 Player of the Year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://calbears.cstv.com/sports/w-volley/mtt/cutura_hana00.html |title=Player Bio: Hana Cutura |website=calbears.cstv.com |accessdate=27 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080914203056/http://calbears.cstv.com/sports/w-volley/mtt/cutura_hana00.html |archivedate=14 September 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IOC profile|zoran-cutura|Zoran Cutura}}\n*[http://www.fiba.basketball/pages/eng/fa/player/p/pid/7913/pid2/7324/sid/2302/tid/390/tid2/2792/_/1979_European_Championship_for_Cadets_Final_Round/index.html FIBA Profile]\n{{KK Cibona 1981\u201382 FIBA European Cup Winner's Cup Champions}}\n{{KK Cibona 1984-85 Euroleague champions}}\n{{KK Cibona 1985-86 Euroleague champions}}\n{{KK Cibona 1986\u201387 FIBA European Cup Winner's Cup Champions}}\n{{Yugoslavia Squad 1986 FIBA World Championship}}\n{{Footer 1988 Olympic Silver Medalists Basketball Men}}\n{{Yugoslavia Squad EuroBasket 1989}}\n{{Yugoslavia Squad 1990 FIBA World Championship}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cutura, Zoran}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Basketball players at the 1988 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Croatian men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:FIBA World Championship-winning players]]\n[[Category:Forwards (basketball)]]\n[[Category:KK Split players]]\n[[Category:KK Cibona players]]\n[[Category:KK Zrinjevac players]]\n[[Category:Olympic basketball players of Yugoslavia]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in basketball]]\n[[Category:Olympic silver medalists for Yugoslavia]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Zagreb]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:1990 FIBA World Championship players]]\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "addCategory:1986 FIBA World Championship playersto player listed at1986 FIBA World Championship squads", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zoran_%C4%8Cutura"}
{"title_page": "Navayana", "text_new": "{{About|a contemporary era Buddhist tradition |book publisher|Navayana (publishing house)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}\n[[File:Buddha Shrine with Ambedkar (244910903).jpg|thumb|Navayana Buddhist shrine with [[Ambedkar]] and [[The Buddha and His Dhamma]] book. The photograph is event of 50th [[Dhammachakra Pravartan Day]].]]\n{{Buddhism}}\n\n'''Navayana''' ([[Devanagari]]: \u0928\u0935\u092f\u093e\u0928, [[IAST]]: ''Navay\u0101na'') means \"new vehicle\" and refers to the re-interpretation of [[Buddhism]] by [[B. R. Ambedkar]].<ref name=\"Robinson2003p192\">{{cite book|author=Gary Tartakov|editor=Rowena Robinson|title=Religious Conversion in India: Modes, Motivations, and Meanings |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eNsoAAAAYAAJ |year=2003|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-566329-7|pages=192\u2013213}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Christopher Queen|editor=Steven M. Emmanuel|title=A Companion to Buddhist Philosophy|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=P_lmCgAAQBAJ |year= 2015|publisher= John Wiley & Sons|isbn= 978-1-119-14466-3|pages=524\u2013525}}</ref> Ambedkar was born in a [[Dalit]] (untouchable) family during the colonial era of India, studied abroad, became a Dalit leader, and announced in 1935 his intent to convert from [[Hinduism]] to Buddhism.<ref name=\"Dirks2011p267\">{{cite book|author=Nicholas B. Dirks|title=Castes of Mind: Colonialism and the Making of Modern India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UP7vmkFSJhIC&pg=PA268|year=2011|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-1-4008-4094-6|pages=267\u2013274}}</ref> Thereafter Ambedkar studied texts of Buddhism and explained properly several of its core beliefs and doctrines such as [[Four Noble Truths]] which were considered as pessimistic and [[Anatta|\"non-self\"]] which appeared contradictory to Buddha's concept of rebirth in his book Buddha and his Dhamma. <ref>{{Cite book|last=Ambedkar, B. R. (Bhimrao Ramji), 1891-1956, author.|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/966360420|title=The Buddha and his dhamma|isbn=978-93-5128-268-6|oclc=966360420}}</ref>This is known as Navayana, also known as '''Bhimay\u0101na''' after Ambedkar's first name Bhimrao.<ref name=\"Jacobsen2015p361\">{{cite book|author=Eleanor Zelliot|editor=Knut A. Jacobsen|title=Routledge Handbook of Contemporary India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tPBWCgAAQBAJ|year=2015|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-317-40357-9|pages=13, 361\u2013370}}</ref> Ambedkar held a press conference on October 13, 1956, announcing his rejection of [[Theravada]] and [[Mahayana]] Buddhism, as well as of Hinduism.<ref name=queen524>{{cite book|author=Christopher Queen|editor=Steven M. Emmanuel|title=A Companion to Buddhist Philosophy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P_lmCgAAQBAJ |year=2015|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-119-14466-3|pages=524\u2013529}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last=Skaria | first=A | title=Ambedkar, Marx and the Buddhist Question | journal= Journal of South Asian Studies | publisher=Taylor & Francis | volume=38 | issue=3 | year=2015 | doi=10.1080/00856401.2015.1049726 | pages=450\u2013452| doi-access=free }}, Quote: \"Here [Navayana Buddhism] there is not only a criticism of religion (most of all, Hinduism, but also prior traditions of Buddhism), but also of secularism, and that criticism is articulated moreover as a religion.\"</ref> Thereafter, he left Hinduism and adopted Navayana, about six weeks before his death.<ref name=\"Robinson2003p192\"/><ref name=\"Jacobsen2015p361\"/><ref name=queen524/>\n\nIn the [[Dalit Buddhist movement]] of India, Navayana is considered a new branch of Buddhism, different from the traditionally recognized branches of [[Theravada]], [[Mahayana]] and [[Vajrayana]].<ref>Omvedt, Gail. Buddhism in India : Challenging Brahmanism and Caste. 3rd ed. London/New Delhi/Thousand Oaks: Sage, 2003. pages: 2, 3\u20137, 8, 14\u201315, 19, 240, 266, 271</ref> Navayana rejects practices and precepts such as renouncing monk and monasticism, karma, rebirth in afterlife, samsara, [[jhana|meditation]], [[nirvana|enlightenment]] and Four Noble Truths considered to be foundational in the Buddhist traditions.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Damien Keown|author2=Charles S. Prebish|title= Encyclopedia of Buddhism |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NFpcAgAAQBAJ |year=2013 |publisher= Routledge|isbn= 978-1-136-98588-1|page=25}}, Quote: \"(...)The Buddhism upon which he settled and about which he wrote in ''The Buddha and His Dhamma'' was, in many respects, unlike any form of Buddhism that had hitherto arisen within the tradition. Gone, for instance, were the doctrines of karma and rebirth, the traditional emphasis on renunciation of the world, the practice of meditation, and the experience of enlightenment. Gone too were any teachings that implied the existence of a trans-empirical realm (...). Most jarring, perhaps, especially among more traditional Buddhists, was the absence of the Four Noble Truths, which Ambedkar regarded as the invention of wrong-headed monks\".</ref> It radically re-interprets what Buddhism is,<ref>{{cite book|author=Bruce Rich|title=To Uphold the World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g-RHBJjU6AoC&pg=PA204|year=2008|publisher=Penguin Books|isbn=978-0-670-99946-0|page=204}}, Quote: Ambedkar's interpretation of Buddhism was a radical one; it took a revisionist approach to a number of widely accepted traditional Buddhist teachings\".</ref> revises the original Buddha teaching to be about [[Class conflict|class struggle]] and social equality.<ref name=\"Jacobsen2015p361\"/><ref name=\"KeownPrebish2013p24\"/><ref name=blackburn1/>\n\nAmbedkar called his version of Buddhism Navayana or '''Neo-Buddhism'''.<ref>{{cite book|author= Christopher S. Queen|title= Engaged Buddhism in the West|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=S7QEAAAAYAAJ|year= 2000|publisher= Wisdom Publications|isbn= 978-0-86171-159-8|page= 23}}</ref> His book, ''[[The Buddha and His Dhamma]]'' is the holy book of Navayana followers. Followers of Navayana Buddhism are generally called \"Buddhists\" (''Baud'dha'') as well as \"Ambedkarite Buddhists\", \"Neo-Buddhists\", and rarely called \"Navayana Buddhists\".<ref>{{cite book|author=Christopher Queen|editor=Steven M. Emmanuel|title=A Companion to Buddhist Philosophy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P_lmCgAAQBAJ |year=2015|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-119-14466-3|pages=524\u2013531}}</ref>\n\n== Origins ==\n[[File:Buddhist flag of Indian Buddhists.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Buddhist flag of Navayana Buddhists]]\nAmbedkar was a [[Dalit]] leader influential during the colonial era and the early post-independence period of India. He was the fourteenth child in an impoverished Maharashtra Dalit family, who studied abroad, returned to India in the 1920s and joined the political movement. His focus was social and political rights for the Dalits.<ref name=\"Buswell2013p34\"/> To free his community from religious prejudice, he concluded that they must leave Hinduism and convert to another religion. He chose Buddhism in the form of Navayana.<ref name=\"Buswell2013p34\">{{cite book|author1=Robert E. Buswell Jr.|author2=Donald S. Lopez Jr.|title=The Princeton Dictionary of Buddhism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DXN2AAAAQBAJ|year=2013|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-1-4008-4805-8|page=34}}</ref><ref name=\"KeownPrebish2013p24\"/>\n\n== Doctrines and concepts ==\nIn 1935, during his disagreements with [[Mahatma Gandhi]], Ambedkar announced his intent to convert from Hinduism to Buddhism.<ref name=\"Dirks2011p267\"/> Over the next two decades, Ambedkar studied texts of Buddhism and concluded that several of the core beliefs and doctrines of mainstream Theravada and Mahayana Buddhism were flawed, pessimistic and a corruption of the Buddha's teachings.<ref name=\"Jacobsen2015p361\"/><ref name=\"KeownPrebish2013p24\"/> In particular, according to [[Eleanor Zelliot]] \u2013 a professor of History specializing on Dalit community in India, Ambedkar found the following beliefs and doctrines of Buddhism as problematic:\n\n;[[Four sights|Buddha's parivaja]]\nThe Buddhist tradition believes that the [[Buddha]] one day saw a sick man, an old man and a dead body in sequence, then he left his princely life and sought insights and a way out of human suffering. According to Ambedkar, this was absurd. He proposed that the Buddha likely sought insights because he was involved in \"making peace among tribes\".<ref name=\"Jacobsen2015p361\"/>\n\n;[[Four Noble Truths]]\nAmbedkar believed that this core doctrine of Buddhism was flawed because it denied hope to human beings. According to Ambedkar, the Four Noble Truths is a \"gospel of pessimism\", and may have been inserted into the Buddhist scriptures by wrong headed Buddhist monks of a later era. These should not be considered as Buddha's teachings in Ambedkar's view.<ref name=\"Jacobsen2015p361\"/><ref name=\"KeownPrebish2013p24\">{{cite book|author1=Damien Keown|author2=Charles S. Prebish|title= Encyclopedia of Buddhism |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NFpcAgAAQBAJ |year=2013 |publisher= Routledge|isbn= 978-1-136-98588-1|pages= 24\u201326}}</ref>\n\n;[[Anatta]], [[Karma]] and [[Reincarnation|Rebirth]] \nThese are other core doctrines of Buddhism. Anatta relates to no-self (no soul) concept. Ambedkar believed that there is an inherent contradiction between the three concepts, either Anatta is incorrect or there cannot be Karma and Rebirth with Anatta in Ambedkar's view.<ref name=\"Jacobsen2015p361\"/> Other foundational concepts of Buddhism such as Karma and Rebirth were considered by Ambedkar as superstitions.<ref name=\"KeownPrebish2013p24\"/>\n\n;[[Bhikshu]]\nA Bhikshu is a member of the monastic practice, a major historic tradition in all schools of Buddhism. According to Ambedkar, this was a flawed idea and practice. He questioned whether a Bhikshu tradition was an attempt to create \"a perfect man or a social servant\", states Zelliot.<ref name=\"Jacobsen2015p361\"/>\n\n;[[Nirvana]]\nAccording to Navayana, nirvana is not some other-worldly state of perfect quietude, freedom, highest happiness, nor soteriological release and liberation from rebirths in [[sa\u1e43s\u0101ra]]. In Ambedkar's view, nirvana is socio-political \"kingdom of righteousness on earth\" in which people are \"freed from poverty and social discrimination and empowered to create themselves happy lives\", state Damien Keown and Charles Prebish.<ref name=\"KeownPrebish2013p24\"/>\n\n== Conversion ==\n[[File:Dr. Ambedkar delivering speech during conversion.jpg|thumb|Ambedkar delivering speech during mass conversion in Nagpur, 14 October 1956.]]\nAmbedkar re-interpreted Buddhism to address such issues in his mind, and re-formulated the traditional teachings of Buddhism into a \"new vehicle\" called Navayana.<ref name=\"Robinson2003p192\"/><ref name=\"Jacobsen2015p361\"/> Navayana dhamma doctrine as propounded by Ambedkar, states Yashwant Sumant, \"does not situate morality in a transcendental [religious] domain\", nor in \"a civil association, including the state\". Dhamma is derived from and the guiding principle for social conscience.<ref>{{cite book|author= Yashwant Sumant| editor1= Surendra Jondhale|editor2= Johannes Beltz| title= Reconstructing the World: B.R. Ambedkar and Buddhism in India|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=K3VuAAAAMAAJ|year= 2004|publisher= Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-566529-1|pages=74\u201375}}</ref>\n\nNavayana Buddhism began in 1956, when B. R. Ambedkar adopted it, and 380,000 Dalit community members converted to Navayana from [[Hinduism]] on 14 and 15 October 1956.<ref name=\"Buswell2013p34\"/><ref name=queen524/> After that on every year 14 October is celebrated as [[Dhammachakra Pravartan Day]] at Dikshabhoomi, Nagpur:\n\n{{quote|I will accept and follow the teachings of Buddha. I will keep my people away from the different opinions of Hinayana and Mahayana, two religious orders. Our Buddhism is a Neo-Buddhism, Navayana.|Babasaheb Ambedkar|Press interview on 13 October 1956 at Sham Hotel, Nagpur<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110208224554/http://www.navayan.com/navayan.php?about-navayan Navayan: Homeland of Ambedkarite Buddhism], Official Website</ref>}}\n\n== Scripture and practice ==\nThe writings of Ambedkar were posthumously published as ''[[The Buddha and His Dhamma]]'', and this is the scripture for those who follow Navayana Buddhism.<ref>{{cite book|author=Christopher Queen|editor=Steven M. Emmanuel|title=A Companion to Buddhist Philosophy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P_lmCgAAQBAJ |year=2015|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-119-14466-3|pages=529\u2013531}}</ref> Among the Navayana followers, state Keown and Prebish, this is \"often referred to as their 'bible' and its novel interpretation of the Buddhist path commonly constitutes their only source of knowledge on the subject.<ref name=\"KeownPrebish2013p24\"/> In this scripture of the Navayana tradition, there are no doctrines of renunciation and monastic life, or [[karma]], or [[Reincarnation#Buddhism|rebirth]], or [[Dhy\u0101na in Buddhism|jhana]] (meditation), or nirvana, or [[Sa\u1e43s\u0101ra (Buddhism)|realms of existence]] or [[Four Noble Truths]] \u2013 ideas found in the major traditions of Buddhism.<ref name=\"KeownPrebish2013p24\"/> The text presents the Buddha as teaching a social empowerment framework. Ambedkar's text on Navayana states that this was what the true Buddha taught and which escapist Buddhist monks had distorted, through misguided interpolations, over Buddhism's long history.<ref name=\"KeownPrebish2013p24\"/>\n\nB. R. Ambedkar is regarded as a [[bodhisattva]], the [[Maitreya]], among the Navayana followers.<ref name=\"Fitzgerald2003\">{{cite book|author= Fitzgerald, Timothy|title= The Ideology of Religious Studies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=R7A1f6Evy84C&pg=PA129| year=2003|publisher= Oxford University Press|isbn= 978-0-19-534715-9|page=129}}</ref><ref name=\"KuldovaVarghese2017\">{{cite book|author=M.B. Bose|editor=Tereza Kuldova and Mathew A. Varghese|title=Urban Utopias: Excess and Expulsion in Neoliberal South Asia |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6c9NDgAAQBAJ&pg=PA144 |year=2017|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-3-319-47623-0|pages=144\u2013146}}</ref> In practice, the Navayana followers revere Ambedkar, states Jim Deitrick, as virtually on par with the Buddha.<ref>{{cite book|author=Jim Deitrick|editor=Damien Keown and Charles S. Prebish|title= Encyclopedia of Buddhism |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=NFpcAgAAQBAJ |year= 2013|publisher= Routledge|isbn= 978-1-136-98588-1|page= 25}}</ref> He is considered as the one prophesied to appear and teach the ''dhamma'' after it was forgotten; his iconography is a part of Navayana shrines and he is shown with a halo.<ref name=\"KuldovaVarghese2017\"/> Though Ambedkar states Navayana to be atheist, Navayana viharas and shrines features images of the Buddha and Ambedkar, and the followers bow and offer prayers before them in practice.<ref>{{cite book|author= Rowena Robinson|title=Religious Conversion in India: Modes, Motivations, and Meanings |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eNsoAAAAYAAJ |year= 2003|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-566329-7|pages=2009 }}</ref> According to Junghare, for the followers of Navayana, Ambedkar has become a deity and is devotionally worshipped.<ref>I.Y. Junghare (1988), [http://nirc.nanzan-u.ac.jp/nfile/1458 Dr. Ambedkar: The Hero of the Mahars, Ex-Untouchables of India], Asian Folklore Studies, 47 (1), 93\u2013121, \"(...) the new literature of the Mahars and their making of the Ambedkar deity for their new religion, Neo-Buddhism. (...) Song five is clearly representative of the Mahar community's respect and devotion for Ambedkar. He has become their God and they worship him as the singer sings: \"We worship Bhima, too.\" (...) In the last song, Dr. Ambedkar is raised from a deity to a supreme deity. He is omnipresent, omnipotent, and omniscient.\"</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n\nAmbedkar's re-interpretation of Buddhism and his formulation of Navayana has attracted admirers and criticism.<ref name=blackburn1>Anne M. Blackburn (1993), [http://journals.ub.uni-heidelberg.de/index.php/jiabs/article/download/8805/2712 Religion, Kinship and Buddhism: Ambedkar's Vision of a Moral Community], The Journal of the International Association of Buddhist Studies 16 (1), 1\u201322</ref> The Navayana theories restate the core doctrines of Buddhism, according to Eleanor Zelliot, wherein Ambedkar's \"social emphasis exclude or distort some teaching, fundamental to traditional and canonical Buddhism\".<ref name=zelliot134>Eleanor Zelliot and Joanna Rogers Macy (1980), Tradition and Innovation in Contemporary Indian Buddhism, in Ed: A.K. Narain, Studies in the History of Buddhism. Delhi: B.R. Publishing, pages 134\u2013142</ref> Anne Blackburn states that Ambedkar re-interprets core concepts of Buddhism in class conflict terms, where [[nirvana]] is not the aim and end of spiritual pursuits, but a preparation for social action against inequality:\n\n{{Quote|\nAmbedkar understands the Buddha's teaching that everything is characterized by [[Dukkha]], or unsatisfactoriness, as referring specifically to interpersonal relations. In one instance Ambedkar presents a dialogue in which the Buddha teaches that the root of dukkha is class conflict and asserts elsewhere that \"the Buddha's conception of Dukkha is material.\" \nNibbana (Skt. [[nirvana]]) the state or process which describes enlightenment, is considered [by Ambedkar] a precursor for moral action in the world and explicitly associated with a non-monastic lifestyle. Nibbana \"means enough control over passion so as to enable one to walk on the path of righteousness.\" Ambedkar's interpretation of dukkha and nibbana implies that moral action, for which nibbana is preparation, will rectify the material suffering of inequality.\n|Anne Blackburn|''Religion, Kinship and Buddhism: Ambedkar's Vision of a Moral Community''<ref name=blackburn1/>}}\n\nAmbedkar considered all ideas in Theravada and Mahayana Buddhism that relate to an individual's merit and spiritual development as insertions into Buddhism, and something that \"cannot be accepted to be the word of the Buddha\". Buddhism, to Ambedkar, must have been a social reform movement.<ref name=blackburn1/><ref name=zelliot134/> Martin Fuchs states that Ambedkar's effort is to be admired as an attempt to seek a \"post-religious religion\" which transcends distinctions and as being driven by the \"reasonable principle of sociality\", not in the sense of spiritual doctrines, philosophical speculations and existentialist questions.<ref>Martin Fuchs (2001), \"A religion for civil society? Ambedkar's Buddhism, the Dalit issue and the imagination of emergent possibilities\", in Editors: Vasudha Dalmia, Angelika Malinar and Martin Christof, Charisma and Canon: Essays on the Religious History of the Indian Subcontinent, Oxford University Press, {{ISBN|978-01956-545-30}}, pages 250\u2013273</ref>\n\nAccording to Blackburn, \"neither view of traditional Buddhism \u2014 as a social reform movement or as some other stable entity interpreted (or misinterpreted) from a social reform perspective \u2014 is historically accurate\", thereby placing Navayana theories to be ahistorical though it served as an important means to Dalit political mobilization and social movement.<ref name=blackburn1/> Scholars broadly accept that the depictions of the Buddha as a caste or social reformer are inaccurate.<ref name=blackburn1/><ref>Y. Krishan (1986), [http://journals.ub.uni-heidelberg.de/index.php/jiabs/article/download/8676/2583 Buddhism and the Caste System], The Journal of the International Association of Buddhist Studies 9 (1), 71\u201384, Quote: \"It has been long recognised that Buddhism and Jainism were not movements for social reform directed against the caste system, and that the Buddha's doctrine did not aim at transformation or improvement of the social conditions.\"</ref> [[Richard Gombrich]], an Indologist and a professor of Buddhist Studies, states that there is no evidence that the Buddha began or pursued social reforms or was against a caste system, rather his aim was at the salvation of those who joined his monastic order.<ref name=gombrich345>{{cite book|author=Richard Gombrich|title=Buddhist Precept & Practice|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lqp4LuZQnHsC |year=2012|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-15623-6 |pages=344\u2013345, context and discussion: 343\u2013370}}</ref><ref>Randall Collins, ''The Sociology of Philosophies: A Global Theory of Intellectual Change.'' Harvard University Press, 2000, page 205-206</ref><ref>{{cite book|author1=Christopher S. Queen|author2=Sallie B. King|title=Engaged Buddhism: Buddhist Liberation Movements in Asia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6ZsTgY1lNNsC&pg=PA17|year=1996|publisher=State University of New York Press|isbn=978-0-7914-2844-3 |pages=17\u201318 }}</ref> Modernist interpreters of Buddhism, states Gombrich, keep picking up this \"mistake from western authors\", a view that initially came into vogue during the colonial era.<ref name=gombrich345/><ref>{{cite book|author=Wanda Alberts|title=Integrative Religious Education in Europe: A Study-of-Religions Approach|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xvwKWS3VKfcC&pg=PA258 |year=2007|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|isbn=978-3-11-097134-7|pages=258\u2013259}}</ref><ref name=\"lopez84\">{{cite book|author=Donald S. Lopez Jr.|title=Buddhism and Science: A Guide for the Perplexed |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M1rTNRb5uA4C |year=2009|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=978-0-226-49324-4|pages=84\u201391}}</ref> Empirical evidence outside of India, such as in the Theravada Buddhist monasteries of the Sinhalese society, suggests that caste ideas have been prevalent among the ''sangha'' monks, and between the Buddhist monks and the laity. In all canonical Buddhist texts, the ''kshatriyas'' (warrior caste) are always mentioned first and never other classes such as ''brahmins'', ''vaishyas'', ''shudras'' or the untouchables.<ref>{{cite book|author=Richard Gombrich|title=Buddhist Precept & Practice|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lqp4LuZQnHsC |year= 2012|publisher= Routledge|isbn= 978-1-136-15623-6|pages= 343\u2013366}}</ref>\n\nThe novel interpretations and the dismissal of mainstream doctrines of Buddhism by Ambedkar as he formulated Navayana has led some to suggest that Navayana may more properly be called Ambedkarism.<ref name=\"KeownPrebish2013p24\"/> However, Ambedkar did not consider himself as the originator of a new Buddhism, but stated that he was merely reviving what was original Buddhism after centuries of \"misguided interpretation\" by wrong headed Buddhist monks.<ref name=\"KeownPrebish2013p24\"/> Others, states Skaria, consider Ambedkar attempting a synthesis of the ideas of modern [[Karl Marx]] into the structure of ideas by the ancient Buddha, as Ambedkar worked on essays on both in the final years of his life.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Skaria | first=A. | title=Ambedkar, Marx and the Buddhist Question | journal= Journal of South Asian Studies | publisher=Taylor & Francis | volume=38 | issue=3 | year=2015 | doi=10.1080/00856401.2015.1049726 | pages=450\u2013465| doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\nAccording to Janet Contursi, Ambedkar re-interprets Buddhist religion and with Navayana \"speaks through Gautama and politicizes the Buddha philosophy as he theologizes his own political views\".<ref>{{cite journal | last=Contursi | first=Janet A. | title=Political Theology: Text and Practice in a Dalit Panther Community | journal=The Journal of Asian Studies | publisher=Cambridge University Press | volume=52 | issue=2 | year=1993 | doi=10.2307/2059650 | pages=320\u2013339| jstor=2059650 }}</ref>\n\n== Status in India ==\n[[File:District wise Buddhist population percentage, India census 2011.png|thumb|District wise Buddhist population percentage, India census 2011. India's West-centre area [[Maharashtra]] shows Navayana [[Marathi Buddhists|Marathi Buddhist]] population]]\n\nAccording to the [[2011 Census of India]] there are 8.4 million Buddhists in India. Navayana Buddhists comprise about 87% (7.3 million) of Indian Buddhist community, and nearly 90% (6.5 million) of all Navayana Buddhists in India live in [[Maharashtra]] state.<ref name=indiaspendnava/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thequint.com/india/2017/06/17/dalits-converting-to-buddhism|title= Manu Moudgil, Dalits Are Still Converting to Buddhism, but at a Dwindling Rate, The Quint, 17.06.17\n|publisher=}}</ref> A 2017 IndiaSpend.com report on census data says \"Buddhists have a literacy rate of 81.29%, higher than the national average of 72.98%\", but it does not distinguish Navayana Buddhists from other Buddhists.<ref name=indiaspendnava>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaspend.com/cover-story/conversion-to-buddhism-has-brought-literacy-gender-equality-and-well-being-to-dalits-18224|title=Conversion To Buddhism Has Brought Literacy, Gender Equality And Well-Being To Dalits \u2013 IndiaSpend-Journalism India -Data Journalism India-Investigative Journalism-IndiaSpend|first=Manu|last=Moudgil|website=www.indiaspend.com}}</ref> When compared to overall literacy rate of Maharashtra state where 80% of Buddhists are found, their literacy rate is 83.17% or slightly higher than statewide average of 82.34%.<ref name=indiaspendnava/>\n\nAccording to Jean Darian, the conversion to Buddhism and its growth in India has in part been because of non-religious factors, in particular the political and economic needs of the community as well as the needs of the political leaders and the expanding administrative structure in India.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Darian | first=Jean C. | title=Social and Economic Factors in the Rise of Buddhism | journal=Sociological Analysis | publisher=Oxford University Press | volume=38 | issue=3 | year=1977 | doi=10.2307/3709803 | pages=226\u2013231| jstor=3709803 }}</ref> According to Trevor Ling and Steven Axelrod, the intellectual and political side of Navayana Buddhist movement lost traction after the death of Ambedkar.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Trevor Ling|author2=Steven Axelrod|title=Buddhist Revival in India: Aspects of the Sociology of Buddhism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Zq2uCwAAQBAJ |year=1980|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|isbn=978-1-349-16310-6|pages=49\u201351}}</ref>\n\n==Festivals==\n[[Ambedkar Jayanti]], [[Dhammachakra Pravartan Day]] and [[Buddha's Birthday]] are three major festivals of Navayana Buddhists.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Buddhism in India]]\n* [[Buddhist modernism]]\n* [[Buddhist socialism]]\n* [[Engaged Buddhism]]\n* [[Humanistic Buddhism]]\n* [[Marathi Buddhists]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite journal|last1=Ambedkar|first1=BR|title=Buddha and the Future of His Religion|journal=The Mah\u00e4-Bodhi|date=1950|volume=58|issue=4\u20135|pages=117\u2013118, 199\u2013206|url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.99895}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Ambedkar|first1=Bhimrao Ramji|last2=Rathore|first2=Aakash Singh|last3=Verma|first3=Ajay (eds)|title=The Buddha and his dhamma: a critical edition|date=2011|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780198068679}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Gannon, Shane P. |title=Conversion as a Thematic Site: Academic Representations of Ambedkar's Buddhist Turn |journal=Method & Theory in the Study of Religion|date=2011 |volume=23 |issue=1 |pages=1\u201328 |jstor=23555728 |doi=10.1163/157006811X549670 }}\n* Jondhale, Surendra;  Beltz, Johannes (2004). Reconstructing the world: B.R. Ambedkar and Buddhism in India, New Delhi : Oxford University Press, {{ISBN|0195665295}}\n* Singh, Aakash (2011). \"The political theology of Navayana Buddhism\", in: P\u00e9ter Losonczi; Mika Luoma-aho; The Future of Political Theology: Religious and Theological Perspectives, Farnham, Surrey, England; Burlington, VT: Ashgate, pp.&nbsp;159\u2013172. {{ISBN|9781409417606}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Navayana}}\n\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20111005221937/http://www.psychotherapieenboeddhisme.nl/documents/bionavupaya2.pdf P.J.C.L. van der Velde, \"The Biography, 'Navayana' as the 'new Vehicle' and Upaya\"], Radboud University, The Netherlands Psychotherapy and Buddhism \n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110719081538/http://eng.buddhapia.com/_Service/_ContentView/ETC_CONTENT_2.ASP?pk=0001378004&sub_pk=&clss_cd=0002204363&top_menu_cd=0000000287&menu_cd=0000008843&menu_code=0000008843 Byung-Jo Chung, \"Navay\u0101na Buddhism: A Fresh Direction for Buddhism to Reflect the New Millenium\"], ''International Journal of Buddhist Thought & Culture,'' (September 2003, Vol. 3).\n\n{{Buddhism topics}}\n{{Religion topics}}\n\n[[Category:Navayana| ]]\n[[Category:B. R. Ambedkar]]\n[[Category:Indian Buddhists]]\n[[Category:Dalit]]\n[[Category:Buddhist new religious movements]]\n[[Category:Buddhism in Maharashtra]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|a contemporary era Buddhist tradition |book publisher|Navayana (publishing house)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}\n[[File:Buddha Shrine with Ambedkar (244910903).jpg|thumb|Navayana Buddhist shrine with [[Ambedkar]] and [[The Buddha and His Dhamma]] book. The photograph is event of 50th [[Dhammachakra Pravartan Day]].]]\n{{Buddhism}}\n\n'''Navayana''' ([[Devanagari]]: \u0928\u0935\u092f\u093e\u0928, [[IAST]]: ''Navay\u0101na'') means \"new vehicle\" and refers to the re-interpretation of [[Buddhism]] by [[B. R. Ambedkar]].<ref name=\"Robinson2003p192\">{{cite book|author=Gary Tartakov|editor=Rowena Robinson|title=Religious Conversion in India: Modes, Motivations, and Meanings |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eNsoAAAAYAAJ |year=2003|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-566329-7|pages=192\u2013213}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Christopher Queen|editor=Steven M. Emmanuel|title=A Companion to Buddhist Philosophy|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=P_lmCgAAQBAJ |year= 2015|publisher= John Wiley & Sons|isbn= 978-1-119-14466-3|pages=524\u2013525}}</ref> Ambedkar was born in a [[Dalit]] (untouchable) family during the colonial era of India, studied abroad, became a Dalit leader, and announced in 1935 his intent to convert from [[Hinduism]] to Buddhism.<ref name=\"Dirks2011p267\">{{cite book|author=Nicholas B. Dirks|title=Castes of Mind: Colonialism and the Making of Modern India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UP7vmkFSJhIC&pg=PA268|year=2011|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-1-4008-4094-6|pages=267\u2013274}}</ref> Thereafter Ambedkar studied texts of Buddhism, found several of its core beliefs and doctrines such as [[Four Noble Truths]] and [[Anatta|\"non-self\"]] as flawed and pessimistic, re-interpreted these into what he called \"new vehicle\" of Buddhism.<ref name=\"Jacobsen2015p361\"/> This is known as Navayana, also known as '''Bhimay\u0101na''' after Ambedkar's first name Bhimrao.<ref name=\"Jacobsen2015p361\">{{cite book|author=Eleanor Zelliot|editor=Knut A. Jacobsen|title=Routledge Handbook of Contemporary India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tPBWCgAAQBAJ|year=2015|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-317-40357-9|pages=13, 361\u2013370}}</ref> Ambedkar held a press conference on October 13, 1956, announcing his rejection of [[Theravada]] and [[Mahayana]] Buddhism, as well as of Hinduism.<ref name=queen524>{{cite book|author=Christopher Queen|editor=Steven M. Emmanuel|title=A Companion to Buddhist Philosophy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P_lmCgAAQBAJ |year=2015|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-119-14466-3|pages=524\u2013529}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last=Skaria | first=A | title=Ambedkar, Marx and the Buddhist Question | journal= Journal of South Asian Studies | publisher=Taylor & Francis | volume=38 | issue=3 | year=2015 | doi=10.1080/00856401.2015.1049726 | pages=450\u2013452| doi-access=free }}, Quote: \"Here [Navayana Buddhism] there is not only a criticism of religion (most of all, Hinduism, but also prior traditions of Buddhism), but also of secularism, and that criticism is articulated moreover as a religion.\"</ref> Thereafter, he left Hinduism and adopted Navayana, about six weeks before his death.<ref name=\"Robinson2003p192\"/><ref name=\"Jacobsen2015p361\"/><ref name=queen524/>\n\nIn the [[Dalit Buddhist movement]] of India, Navayana is considered a new branch of Buddhism, different from the traditionally recognized branches of [[Theravada]], [[Mahayana]] and [[Vajrayana]].<ref>Omvedt, Gail. Buddhism in India : Challenging Brahmanism and Caste. 3rd ed. London/New Delhi/Thousand Oaks: Sage, 2003. pages: 2, 3\u20137, 8, 14\u201315, 19, 240, 266, 271</ref> Navayana rejects practices and precepts such as renouncing monk and monasticism, karma, rebirth in afterlife, samsara, [[jhana|meditation]], [[nirvana|enlightenment]] and Four Noble Truths considered to be foundational in the Buddhist traditions.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Damien Keown|author2=Charles S. Prebish|title= Encyclopedia of Buddhism |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NFpcAgAAQBAJ |year=2013 |publisher= Routledge|isbn= 978-1-136-98588-1|page=25}}, Quote: \"(...)The Buddhism upon which he settled and about which he wrote in ''The Buddha and His Dhamma'' was, in many respects, unlike any form of Buddhism that had hitherto arisen within the tradition. Gone, for instance, were the doctrines of karma and rebirth, the traditional emphasis on renunciation of the world, the practice of meditation, and the experience of enlightenment. Gone too were any teachings that implied the existence of a trans-empirical realm (...). Most jarring, perhaps, especially among more traditional Buddhists, was the absence of the Four Noble Truths, which Ambedkar regarded as the invention of wrong-headed monks\".</ref> It radically re-interprets what Buddhism is,<ref>{{cite book|author=Bruce Rich|title=To Uphold the World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g-RHBJjU6AoC&pg=PA204|year=2008|publisher=Penguin Books|isbn=978-0-670-99946-0|page=204}}, Quote: Ambedkar's interpretation of Buddhism was a radical one; it took a revisionist approach to a number of widely accepted traditional Buddhist teachings\".</ref> revises the original Buddha teaching to be about [[Class conflict|class struggle]] and social equality.<ref name=\"Jacobsen2015p361\"/><ref name=\"KeownPrebish2013p24\"/><ref name=blackburn1/>\n\nAmbedkar called his version of Buddhism Navayana or '''Neo-Buddhism'''.<ref>{{cite book|author= Christopher S. Queen|title= Engaged Buddhism in the West|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=S7QEAAAAYAAJ|year= 2000|publisher= Wisdom Publications|isbn= 978-0-86171-159-8|page= 23}}</ref> His book, ''[[The Buddha and His Dhamma]]'' is the holy book of Navayana followers. Followers of Navayana Buddhism are generally called \"Buddhists\" (''Baud'dha'') as well as \"Ambedkarite Buddhists\", \"Neo-Buddhists\", and rarely called \"Navayana Buddhists\".<ref>{{cite book|author=Christopher Queen|editor=Steven M. Emmanuel|title=A Companion to Buddhist Philosophy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P_lmCgAAQBAJ |year=2015|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-119-14466-3|pages=524\u2013531}}</ref>\n\n== Origins ==\n[[File:Buddhist flag of Indian Buddhists.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Buddhist flag of Navayana Buddhists]]\nAmbedkar was a [[Dalit]] leader influential during the colonial era and the early post-independence period of India. He was the fourteenth child in an impoverished Maharashtra Dalit family, who studied abroad, returned to India in the 1920s and joined the political movement. His focus was social and political rights for the Dalits.<ref name=\"Buswell2013p34\"/> To free his community from religious prejudice, he concluded that they must leave Hinduism and convert to another religion. He chose Buddhism in the form of Navayana.<ref name=\"Buswell2013p34\">{{cite book|author1=Robert E. Buswell Jr.|author2=Donald S. Lopez Jr.|title=The Princeton Dictionary of Buddhism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DXN2AAAAQBAJ|year=2013|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-1-4008-4805-8|page=34}}</ref><ref name=\"KeownPrebish2013p24\"/>\n\n== Doctrines and concepts ==\nIn 1935, during his disagreements with [[Mahatma Gandhi]], Ambedkar announced his intent to convert from Hinduism to Buddhism.<ref name=\"Dirks2011p267\"/> Over the next two decades, Ambedkar studied texts of Buddhism and concluded that several of the core beliefs and doctrines of mainstream Theravada and Mahayana Buddhism were flawed, pessimistic and a corruption of the Buddha's teachings.<ref name=\"Jacobsen2015p361\"/><ref name=\"KeownPrebish2013p24\"/> In particular, according to [[Eleanor Zelliot]] \u2013 a professor of History specializing on Dalit community in India, Ambedkar found the following beliefs and doctrines of Buddhism as problematic:\n\n;[[Four sights|Buddha's parivaja]]\nThe Buddhist tradition believes that the [[Buddha]] one day saw a sick man, an old man and a dead body in sequence, then he left his princely life and sought insights and a way out of human suffering. According to Ambedkar, this was absurd. He proposed that the Buddha likely sought insights because he was involved in \"making peace among tribes\".<ref name=\"Jacobsen2015p361\"/>\n\n;[[Four Noble Truths]]\nAmbedkar believed that this core doctrine of Buddhism was flawed because it denied hope to human beings. According to Ambedkar, the Four Noble Truths is a \"gospel of pessimism\", and may have been inserted into the Buddhist scriptures by wrong headed Buddhist monks of a later era. These should not be considered as Buddha's teachings in Ambedkar's view.<ref name=\"Jacobsen2015p361\"/><ref name=\"KeownPrebish2013p24\">{{cite book|author1=Damien Keown|author2=Charles S. Prebish|title= Encyclopedia of Buddhism |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NFpcAgAAQBAJ |year=2013 |publisher= Routledge|isbn= 978-1-136-98588-1|pages= 24\u201326}}</ref>\n\n;[[Anatta]], [[Karma]] and [[Reincarnation|Rebirth]] \nThese are other core doctrines of Buddhism. Anatta relates to no-self (no soul) concept. Ambedkar believed that there is an inherent contradiction between the three concepts, either Anatta is incorrect or there cannot be Karma and Rebirth with Anatta in Ambedkar's view.<ref name=\"Jacobsen2015p361\"/> Other foundational concepts of Buddhism such as Karma and Rebirth were considered by Ambedkar as superstitions.<ref name=\"KeownPrebish2013p24\"/>\n\n;[[Bhikshu]]\nA Bhikshu is a member of the monastic practice, a major historic tradition in all schools of Buddhism. According to Ambedkar, this was a flawed idea and practice. He questioned whether a Bhikshu tradition was an attempt to create \"a perfect man or a social servant\", states Zelliot.<ref name=\"Jacobsen2015p361\"/>\n\n;[[Nirvana]]\nAccording to Navayana, nirvana is not some other-worldly state of perfect quietude, freedom, highest happiness, nor soteriological release and liberation from rebirths in [[sa\u1e43s\u0101ra]]. In Ambedkar's view, nirvana is socio-political \"kingdom of righteousness on earth\" in which people are \"freed from poverty and social discrimination and empowered to create themselves happy lives\", state Damien Keown and Charles Prebish.<ref name=\"KeownPrebish2013p24\"/>\n\n== Conversion ==\n[[File:Dr. Ambedkar delivering speech during conversion.jpg|thumb|Ambedkar delivering speech during mass conversion in Nagpur, 14 October 1956.]]\nAmbedkar re-interpreted Buddhism to address such issues in his mind, and re-formulated the traditional teachings of Buddhism into a \"new vehicle\" called Navayana.<ref name=\"Robinson2003p192\"/><ref name=\"Jacobsen2015p361\"/> Navayana dhamma doctrine as propounded by Ambedkar, states Yashwant Sumant, \"does not situate morality in a transcendental [religious] domain\", nor in \"a civil association, including the state\". Dhamma is derived from and the guiding principle for social conscience.<ref>{{cite book|author= Yashwant Sumant| editor1= Surendra Jondhale|editor2= Johannes Beltz| title= Reconstructing the World: B.R. Ambedkar and Buddhism in India|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=K3VuAAAAMAAJ|year= 2004|publisher= Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-566529-1|pages=74\u201375}}</ref>\n\nNavayana Buddhism began in 1956, when B. R. Ambedkar adopted it, and 380,000 Dalit community members converted to Navayana from [[Hinduism]] on 14 and 15 October 1956.<ref name=\"Buswell2013p34\"/><ref name=queen524/> After that on every year 14 October is celebrated as [[Dhammachakra Pravartan Day]] at Dikshabhoomi, Nagpur:\n\n{{quote|I will accept and follow the teachings of Buddha. I will keep my people away from the different opinions of Hinayana and Mahayana, two religious orders. Our Buddhism is a Neo-Buddhism, Navayana.|Babasaheb Ambedkar|Press interview on 13 October 1956 at Sham Hotel, Nagpur<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110208224554/http://www.navayan.com/navayan.php?about-navayan Navayan: Homeland of Ambedkarite Buddhism], Official Website</ref>}}\n\n== Scripture and practice ==\nThe writings of Ambedkar were posthumously published as ''[[The Buddha and His Dhamma]]'', and this is the scripture for those who follow Navayana Buddhism.<ref>{{cite book|author=Christopher Queen|editor=Steven M. Emmanuel|title=A Companion to Buddhist Philosophy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P_lmCgAAQBAJ |year=2015|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-119-14466-3|pages=529\u2013531}}</ref> Among the Navayana followers, state Keown and Prebish, this is \"often referred to as their 'bible' and its novel interpretation of the Buddhist path commonly constitutes their only source of knowledge on the subject.<ref name=\"KeownPrebish2013p24\"/> In this scripture of the Navayana tradition, there are no doctrines of renunciation and monastic life, or [[karma]], or [[Reincarnation#Buddhism|rebirth]], or [[Dhy\u0101na in Buddhism|jhana]] (meditation), or nirvana, or [[Sa\u1e43s\u0101ra (Buddhism)|realms of existence]] or [[Four Noble Truths]] \u2013 ideas found in the major traditions of Buddhism.<ref name=\"KeownPrebish2013p24\"/> The text presents the Buddha as teaching a social empowerment framework. Ambedkar's text on Navayana states that this was what the true Buddha taught and which escapist Buddhist monks had distorted, through misguided interpolations, over Buddhism's long history.<ref name=\"KeownPrebish2013p24\"/>\n\nB. R. Ambedkar is regarded as a [[bodhisattva]], the [[Maitreya]], among the Navayana followers.<ref name=\"Fitzgerald2003\">{{cite book|author= Fitzgerald, Timothy|title= The Ideology of Religious Studies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=R7A1f6Evy84C&pg=PA129| year=2003|publisher= Oxford University Press|isbn= 978-0-19-534715-9|page=129}}</ref><ref name=\"KuldovaVarghese2017\">{{cite book|author=M.B. Bose|editor=Tereza Kuldova and Mathew A. Varghese|title=Urban Utopias: Excess and Expulsion in Neoliberal South Asia |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6c9NDgAAQBAJ&pg=PA144 |year=2017|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-3-319-47623-0|pages=144\u2013146}}</ref> In practice, the Navayana followers revere Ambedkar, states Jim Deitrick, as virtually on par with the Buddha.<ref>{{cite book|author=Jim Deitrick|editor=Damien Keown and Charles S. Prebish|title= Encyclopedia of Buddhism |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=NFpcAgAAQBAJ |year= 2013|publisher= Routledge|isbn= 978-1-136-98588-1|page= 25}}</ref> He is considered as the one prophesied to appear and teach the ''dhamma'' after it was forgotten; his iconography is a part of Navayana shrines and he is shown with a halo.<ref name=\"KuldovaVarghese2017\"/> Though Ambedkar states Navayana to be atheist, Navayana viharas and shrines features images of the Buddha and Ambedkar, and the followers bow and offer prayers before them in practice.<ref>{{cite book|author= Rowena Robinson|title=Religious Conversion in India: Modes, Motivations, and Meanings |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eNsoAAAAYAAJ |year= 2003|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-566329-7|pages=2009 }}</ref> According to Junghare, for the followers of Navayana, Ambedkar has become a deity and is devotionally worshipped.<ref>I.Y. Junghare (1988), [http://nirc.nanzan-u.ac.jp/nfile/1458 Dr. Ambedkar: The Hero of the Mahars, Ex-Untouchables of India], Asian Folklore Studies, 47 (1), 93\u2013121, \"(...) the new literature of the Mahars and their making of the Ambedkar deity for their new religion, Neo-Buddhism. (...) Song five is clearly representative of the Mahar community's respect and devotion for Ambedkar. He has become their God and they worship him as the singer sings: \"We worship Bhima, too.\" (...) In the last song, Dr. Ambedkar is raised from a deity to a supreme deity. He is omnipresent, omnipotent, and omniscient.\"</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n\nAmbedkar's re-interpretation of Buddhism and his formulation of Navayana has attracted admirers and criticism.<ref name=blackburn1>Anne M. Blackburn (1993), [http://journals.ub.uni-heidelberg.de/index.php/jiabs/article/download/8805/2712 Religion, Kinship and Buddhism: Ambedkar's Vision of a Moral Community], The Journal of the International Association of Buddhist Studies 16 (1), 1\u201322</ref> The Navayana theories restate the core doctrines of Buddhism, according to Eleanor Zelliot, wherein Ambedkar's \"social emphasis exclude or distort some teaching, fundamental to traditional and canonical Buddhism\".<ref name=zelliot134>Eleanor Zelliot and Joanna Rogers Macy (1980), Tradition and Innovation in Contemporary Indian Buddhism, in Ed: A.K. Narain, Studies in the History of Buddhism. Delhi: B.R. Publishing, pages 134\u2013142</ref> Anne Blackburn states that Ambedkar re-interprets core concepts of Buddhism in class conflict terms, where [[nirvana]] is not the aim and end of spiritual pursuits, but a preparation for social action against inequality:\n\n{{Quote|\nAmbedkar understands the Buddha's teaching that everything is characterized by [[Dukkha]], or unsatisfactoriness, as referring specifically to interpersonal relations. In one instance Ambedkar presents a dialogue in which the Buddha teaches that the root of dukkha is class conflict and asserts elsewhere that \"the Buddha's conception of Dukkha is material.\" \nNibbana (Skt. [[nirvana]]) the state or process which describes enlightenment, is considered [by Ambedkar] a precursor for moral action in the world and explicitly associated with a non-monastic lifestyle. Nibbana \"means enough control over passion so as to enable one to walk on the path of righteousness.\" Ambedkar's interpretation of dukkha and nibbana implies that moral action, for which nibbana is preparation, will rectify the material suffering of inequality.\n|Anne Blackburn|''Religion, Kinship and Buddhism: Ambedkar's Vision of a Moral Community''<ref name=blackburn1/>}}\n\nAmbedkar considered all ideas in Theravada and Mahayana Buddhism that relate to an individual's merit and spiritual development as insertions into Buddhism, and something that \"cannot be accepted to be the word of the Buddha\". Buddhism, to Ambedkar, must have been a social reform movement.<ref name=blackburn1/><ref name=zelliot134/> Martin Fuchs states that Ambedkar's effort is to be admired as an attempt to seek a \"post-religious religion\" which transcends distinctions and as being driven by the \"reasonable principle of sociality\", not in the sense of spiritual doctrines, philosophical speculations and existentialist questions.<ref>Martin Fuchs (2001), \"A religion for civil society? Ambedkar's Buddhism, the Dalit issue and the imagination of emergent possibilities\", in Editors: Vasudha Dalmia, Angelika Malinar and Martin Christof, Charisma and Canon: Essays on the Religious History of the Indian Subcontinent, Oxford University Press, {{ISBN|978-01956-545-30}}, pages 250\u2013273</ref>\n\nAccording to Blackburn, \"neither view of traditional Buddhism \u2014 as a social reform movement or as some other stable entity interpreted (or misinterpreted) from a social reform perspective \u2014 is historically accurate\", thereby placing Navayana theories to be ahistorical though it served as an important means to Dalit political mobilization and social movement.<ref name=blackburn1/> Scholars broadly accept that the depictions of the Buddha as a caste or social reformer are inaccurate.<ref name=blackburn1/><ref>Y. Krishan (1986), [http://journals.ub.uni-heidelberg.de/index.php/jiabs/article/download/8676/2583 Buddhism and the Caste System], The Journal of the International Association of Buddhist Studies 9 (1), 71\u201384, Quote: \"It has been long recognised that Buddhism and Jainism were not movements for social reform directed against the caste system, and that the Buddha's doctrine did not aim at transformation or improvement of the social conditions.\"</ref> [[Richard Gombrich]], an Indologist and a professor of Buddhist Studies, states that there is no evidence that the Buddha began or pursued social reforms or was against a caste system, rather his aim was at the salvation of those who joined his monastic order.<ref name=gombrich345>{{cite book|author=Richard Gombrich|title=Buddhist Precept & Practice|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lqp4LuZQnHsC |year=2012|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-15623-6 |pages=344\u2013345, context and discussion: 343\u2013370}}</ref><ref>Randall Collins, ''The Sociology of Philosophies: A Global Theory of Intellectual Change.'' Harvard University Press, 2000, page 205-206</ref><ref>{{cite book|author1=Christopher S. Queen|author2=Sallie B. King|title=Engaged Buddhism: Buddhist Liberation Movements in Asia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6ZsTgY1lNNsC&pg=PA17|year=1996|publisher=State University of New York Press|isbn=978-0-7914-2844-3 |pages=17\u201318 }}</ref> Modernist interpreters of Buddhism, states Gombrich, keep picking up this \"mistake from western authors\", a view that initially came into vogue during the colonial era.<ref name=gombrich345/><ref>{{cite book|author=Wanda Alberts|title=Integrative Religious Education in Europe: A Study-of-Religions Approach|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xvwKWS3VKfcC&pg=PA258 |year=2007|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|isbn=978-3-11-097134-7|pages=258\u2013259}}</ref><ref name=\"lopez84\">{{cite book|author=Donald S. Lopez Jr.|title=Buddhism and Science: A Guide for the Perplexed |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M1rTNRb5uA4C |year=2009|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=978-0-226-49324-4|pages=84\u201391}}</ref> Empirical evidence outside of India, such as in the Theravada Buddhist monasteries of the Sinhalese society, suggests that caste ideas have been prevalent among the ''sangha'' monks, and between the Buddhist monks and the laity. In all canonical Buddhist texts, the ''kshatriyas'' (warrior caste) are always mentioned first and never other classes such as ''brahmins'', ''vaishyas'', ''shudras'' or the untouchables.<ref>{{cite book|author=Richard Gombrich|title=Buddhist Precept & Practice|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lqp4LuZQnHsC |year= 2012|publisher= Routledge|isbn= 978-1-136-15623-6|pages= 343\u2013366}}</ref>\n\nThe novel interpretations and the dismissal of mainstream doctrines of Buddhism by Ambedkar as he formulated Navayana has led some to suggest that Navayana may more properly be called Ambedkarism.<ref name=\"KeownPrebish2013p24\"/> However, Ambedkar did not consider himself as the originator of a new Buddhism, but stated that he was merely reviving what was original Buddhism after centuries of \"misguided interpretation\" by wrong headed Buddhist monks.<ref name=\"KeownPrebish2013p24\"/> Others, states Skaria, consider Ambedkar attempting a synthesis of the ideas of modern [[Karl Marx]] into the structure of ideas by the ancient Buddha, as Ambedkar worked on essays on both in the final years of his life.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Skaria | first=A. | title=Ambedkar, Marx and the Buddhist Question | journal= Journal of South Asian Studies | publisher=Taylor & Francis | volume=38 | issue=3 | year=2015 | doi=10.1080/00856401.2015.1049726 | pages=450\u2013465| doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\nAccording to Janet Contursi, Ambedkar re-interprets Buddhist religion and with Navayana \"speaks through Gautama and politicizes the Buddha philosophy as he theologizes his own political views\".<ref>{{cite journal | last=Contursi | first=Janet A. | title=Political Theology: Text and Practice in a Dalit Panther Community | journal=The Journal of Asian Studies | publisher=Cambridge University Press | volume=52 | issue=2 | year=1993 | doi=10.2307/2059650 | pages=320\u2013339| jstor=2059650 }}</ref>\n\n== Status in India ==\n[[File:District wise Buddhist population percentage, India census 2011.png|thumb|District wise Buddhist population percentage, India census 2011. India's West-centre area [[Maharashtra]] shows Navayana [[Marathi Buddhists|Marathi Buddhist]] population]]\n\nAccording to the [[2011 Census of India]] there are 8.4 million Buddhists in India. Navayana Buddhists comprise about 87% (7.3 million) of Indian Buddhist community, and nearly 90% (6.5 million) of all Navayana Buddhists in India live in [[Maharashtra]] state.<ref name=indiaspendnava/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thequint.com/india/2017/06/17/dalits-converting-to-buddhism|title= Manu Moudgil, Dalits Are Still Converting to Buddhism, but at a Dwindling Rate, The Quint, 17.06.17\n|publisher=}}</ref> A 2017 IndiaSpend.com report on census data says \"Buddhists have a literacy rate of 81.29%, higher than the national average of 72.98%\", but it does not distinguish Navayana Buddhists from other Buddhists.<ref name=indiaspendnava>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaspend.com/cover-story/conversion-to-buddhism-has-brought-literacy-gender-equality-and-well-being-to-dalits-18224|title=Conversion To Buddhism Has Brought Literacy, Gender Equality And Well-Being To Dalits \u2013 IndiaSpend-Journalism India -Data Journalism India-Investigative Journalism-IndiaSpend|first=Manu|last=Moudgil|website=www.indiaspend.com}}</ref> When compared to overall literacy rate of Maharashtra state where 80% of Buddhists are found, their literacy rate is 83.17% or slightly higher than statewide average of 82.34%.<ref name=indiaspendnava/>\n\nAccording to Jean Darian, the conversion to Buddhism and its growth in India has in part been because of non-religious factors, in particular the political and economic needs of the community as well as the needs of the political leaders and the expanding administrative structure in India.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Darian | first=Jean C. | title=Social and Economic Factors in the Rise of Buddhism | journal=Sociological Analysis | publisher=Oxford University Press | volume=38 | issue=3 | year=1977 | doi=10.2307/3709803 | pages=226\u2013231| jstor=3709803 }}</ref> According to Trevor Ling and Steven Axelrod, the intellectual and political side of Navayana Buddhist movement lost traction after the death of Ambedkar.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Trevor Ling|author2=Steven Axelrod|title=Buddhist Revival in India: Aspects of the Sociology of Buddhism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Zq2uCwAAQBAJ |year=1980|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|isbn=978-1-349-16310-6|pages=49\u201351}}</ref>\n\n==Festivals==\n[[Ambedkar Jayanti]], [[Dhammachakra Pravartan Day]] and [[Buddha's Birthday]] are three major festivals of Navayana Buddhists.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Buddhism in India]]\n* [[Buddhist modernism]]\n* [[Buddhist socialism]]\n* [[Engaged Buddhism]]\n* [[Humanistic Buddhism]]\n* [[Marathi Buddhists]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite journal|last1=Ambedkar|first1=BR|title=Buddha and the Future of His Religion|journal=The Mah\u00e4-Bodhi|date=1950|volume=58|issue=4\u20135|pages=117\u2013118, 199\u2013206|url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.99895}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Ambedkar|first1=Bhimrao Ramji|last2=Rathore|first2=Aakash Singh|last3=Verma|first3=Ajay (eds)|title=The Buddha and his dhamma: a critical edition|date=2011|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780198068679}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Gannon, Shane P. |title=Conversion as a Thematic Site: Academic Representations of Ambedkar's Buddhist Turn |journal=Method & Theory in the Study of Religion|date=2011 |volume=23 |issue=1 |pages=1\u201328 |jstor=23555728 |doi=10.1163/157006811X549670 }}\n* Jondhale, Surendra;  Beltz, Johannes (2004). Reconstructing the world: B.R. Ambedkar and Buddhism in India, New Delhi : Oxford University Press, {{ISBN|0195665295}}\n* Singh, Aakash (2011). \"The political theology of Navayana Buddhism\", in: P\u00e9ter Losonczi; Mika Luoma-aho; The Future of Political Theology: Religious and Theological Perspectives, Farnham, Surrey, England; Burlington, VT: Ashgate, pp.&nbsp;159\u2013172. {{ISBN|9781409417606}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Navayana}}\n\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20111005221937/http://www.psychotherapieenboeddhisme.nl/documents/bionavupaya2.pdf P.J.C.L. van der Velde, \"The Biography, 'Navayana' as the 'new Vehicle' and Upaya\"], Radboud University, The Netherlands Psychotherapy and Buddhism \n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110719081538/http://eng.buddhapia.com/_Service/_ContentView/ETC_CONTENT_2.ASP?pk=0001378004&sub_pk=&clss_cd=0002204363&top_menu_cd=0000000287&menu_cd=0000008843&menu_code=0000008843 Byung-Jo Chung, \"Navay\u0101na Buddhism: A Fresh Direction for Buddhism to Reflect the New Millenium\"], ''International Journal of Buddhist Thought & Culture,'' (September 2003, Vol. 3).\n\n{{Buddhism topics}}\n{{Religion topics}}\n\n[[Category:Navayana| ]]\n[[Category:B. R. Ambedkar]]\n[[Category:Indian Buddhists]]\n[[Category:Dalit]]\n[[Category:Buddhist new religious movements]]\n[[Category:Buddhism in Maharashtra]]\